8089. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 32172031
T1  - Cataract surgery with rigid and foldable posterior chamber IOLs, ECCE and phacoemulsification
A1  - Anonymous.
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - The modern era of extracapsular cataract surgery (generation VI) began in about 1987 (Fig. 6.2), simultaneous with the trend toward in-the-bag fixation. We are enjoying the fruits of this today. The incidence of the two major complications of the ECCE-PC-IOL procedure, decentration and PCO (see Chapter 7), are now finally diminishing, if not totally disappearing. The era, characterized by 1) improved surgical techniques that enhance cataract removal (viscoelastic, CCC, hydrodissection, better ECCE or phacoemulsification [Table 6.1]); 2) more success in placing the IOL in-the-bag; and 3) availability f better designed and manufactured and more biocompatible IOLs (rigid and foldable) is well established in the industrialized world. The process has been delayed for about a decade in the developing world (Fig. 6.3). However, as conditions improve, surgeons in the developing world are beginning to progressively apply these modern techniques (Fig. 6.4). Selected centers are now able to apply modern ECCE techniques and all are implanting the most modern available one-piece all-PMMA capsular IOLs. One must forget, however, that these successes represent only a beginning. There are few facilities that are well equipped and subsidized with surgeons. It will take time to implement these successes on a widespread basis. The goal of this chapter has been to help inform the developing-world surgeon regarding the implementation of various techniques and factors that will enable him or her to continue to progress toward the right of the scale shown in Figs. 6.3 and 6.4 and Table 6.1, i.e. from generation V-a via the transition phase V-b on toward generation VI. There is no doubt that as this shift continues, especially in hospitals or surgical centers, phacoemulsification will become a common procedure (generation VI-b). However, in a developing world setting, the basic goal is to cure significant blindness. Therefore, dependence on highly sophisticated modern techniques, especially insertion of foldable IOLs through a small incision after phacoemulsification (generation VI-b), is not an urgent requirement of the highest order. The small-incision procedure now prevalent in the industrialized world provides additional subtle advantages including faster recovery and less astigmatism, items less related to basic safety. The main advantage of the modern capsular techniques in generations VI-a and VI-b is to provide a safe and permanent IOL fixation. In poorer rural field situations, a trend toward high-quality ECCE with continued use of large incision and high-quality rigid PMMA lenses (VI-a) will be more than satisfactory to achieve the desired results. Improved surgical results can only occur after better training is available and as appropriate gadgetry in the operating room is accumulated. An example of a typical problem is the fact that day-to-day maintenance of an operating microscope with coaxial illumination is often difficult or impossible. However, the time has come, since our technology and expertise have improved, to fine tune the technology and provide it to surgeons in the rural developing world. It is noteworthy that generation V-a, (Table 6.1, Fig. 6.2), often termed the "simple ECCE-IOL procedure" in developing-world nomenclature, has virtually disappeared from the surgeon's armamentarium in the industrialized world. This began in about 1992. In the USA fewer than 5% of surgeons use classic large-incision techniques; well over 90% have turned to phacoemulsification. In order for similar results to be achieved on a massive scale in the vast rural underdeveloped world, the "simple ECCE" phase must quickly pass and development of improved ECCE techniques (generation V-b) and transition to generation VI needs to occur. In the past this was unheard of in the rural developing world setting. Now it needs to be contemplated, advocated, and accomplished.
