T1  - Endometrial biopsy
A1  - Apgar B.S.
A1  - Newkirk G.R. 
Y1  - 1997//
N2  - Endometrial biopsy is a safe, efficient, and relatively painless procedure. Primary indications include AUB and evaluation of infertility. For those patients with AUB, ruling out endometrial cancer and precursors is of primary concern. Patients with risk factors such as obesity, chronic anovulation, and use of unopposed estrogen should be evaluated aggressively if AUB is present. Evaluation of a short luteal phase can be accomplished effectively with a timed endometrial sample in infertility patients. The technique of endometrial biopsy is straightforward and is accomplished in a minimal amount of time. The most commonly used sampling device is the polyethylene aspirator, and sensitivity approaches 95% for the diagnosis of endometrial cancer. Inadequate samples account for a high percentage of samples in postmenopausal women, primarily owing to atrophy. The presence of cytologic atypia and hyperplasia on histology represents a true cancer precursor state.
