8170. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 30048178
T1  - Effect of obesity on fertility
A1  - Pasquali R. 
Y1  - 1999//
N2  - Obesity negatively affects fertility in premenopausal women by mechanisms which involve altered androgen secretion, transport and metabolism. An example of this interaction is represented by the common association between obesity and the polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Obesity in fact may play a specific and independent role in the development of PCOS in susceptible individuals, by mechanisms possibly related to specific intrauterine and/or pubertal factors. This is further emphasized by the fact that obese PCOS women are characterized by several distinct hormonal, anthropometric, metabolic and clinical features with respect to their nonobese counterpart. Hyperinsulinemia and insulin resistance are commonly present in PCOS and are believed to play an important pathogenetic role in the development of hyperandrogenism. In fact, insulin possesses a true gonadotropic effect, which synergizes the action of gonadotropins. Obesity, particularly the abdominal/visceral phenotype, is a typical insulin resistant and hyperinsulinemic state and, consequently, the association with hyperandrogenism in women with PCOS can be easily explained in this way. On the other hand, other hormonal and non hormonal factors may be involved in this context. Correction of hyperinsulinemia by dietary-induced weight loss and/or the administration of insulin-sensitizers (which can reduce circulating insulin levels) may be effective in the treatment of PCOS, since it can improve metabolic abnormalities and hyperandrogenism and related clinical features, including anovulation and menstrual abnormalities.
