8183. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 30168853
T1  - The role of laparoscopic ovarian electrocautery in the new millennium
A1  - Donesky B.W. 
Y1  - 1999//
N2  - In anovulatory women resistant to clomiphene citrate, surgical procedures designed to achieve partial destruction of the ovary are able to produce ovulation in the vast majority of cases. Overall, pregnancy occurs in approximately 55-60% of women so treated. The incidence of adhesion formation is high, with controlled studies showing that incidence to be as high as 80%. Nevertheless, in spite of the high incidence of adhesion formation, overall pregnancy rates appear to compare favourably to those reported for gonadotrophin ovulation induction. While most authors report that a substantial proportion of patients will resume their anovulatory menstrual pattern within 12 months of the surgery, others have found the majority of their patients to continue with ovulatory cycles for up to 20 years. Since these are relatively new procedures, the issues surrounding the potential for decreasing ovarian reserve or causing premature entry into menopause have not been adequately assessed at this time. While retrospective data concerning BOWR suggest that young women who underwent BOWR before they were 30 years old underwent menopause up to 10 years earlier than controls, the only long-term series on laparoscopic electrocautery suggests no significant effect of these procedures upon the onset of menopause. While these procedures can and do help many women achieve pregnancy, several newer and less invasive techniques are under investigation and are also promising. These include transvaginal interstitial laser treatment (TILT), cryosurgery and prolonged ovarian suppression with GnRH agonists and OC's. The study of the connection between insulin resistance and PCOS has provided the potential for additional medical adjuvants to ovulation induction that may eventually make surgical methods of ovulation induction obsolete.
