8200. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 28379305
T1  - Genetic and environmental origins of polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Norman R.J.
A1  - Huber-Buchholz M.-M.
A1  - Hague W.M. 
Y1  - 1998//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is one of the commonest endocrine conditions in women of reproductive age and has a heterogeneous presentation. The etiology of the condition is unknown but it is clear that there are potentially significant contributions from both genetic and environmentally-determined elements. Familial. Some types of PC0S occur in families but the form of inheritance is contested. Recent reports have suggested an autosomal dominant inheritance but there are considerable assumptions made in proposing this pattern. Studies in twin pairs have not supported a genetic component to the familial occurrence of PCOS. Steroid synthesis abnormalities. Dysregulation of androgen secretion, particularly that affecting 17-hydroxylase and 17,20 lyase activity in the ovary, is supported by observations of increased circulating androgens and altered steroid precursors following gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) agonist-induced elevation of luteinizing hormone (LH). Genetic and insulin-mediated effects on the activity of this enzyme have both been documented. Insulin. Insulin resistance is abnormal in obese and anovulatory subjects with PCOS despite a normal structure of the insulin receptor in the majority of women. Abnormal post-receptor function has been reported in some subjects. Obesity. Excessive body mass is seen in over 50% of women with PCOS and there is a higher prevalence of upper body fat distribution. Weight loss and reduction in waist circumference are associated with return of reproductive function in anovulatory women, in association with changes in insulin sensitivity that predate improvement in ovarian activity Leptin concentrations are increased in obese women but it is uncertain whether there are inappropriately increased concentrations.
