A1  - Out H.J.
A1  - Coelingh Bennink H.J.T. 
Y1  - 1998//
N2  - Background: Clomiphene citrate is an antiestrogenic compound and one of the most prescribed infertility drugs. However, its mechanism of action and potential to cause side effects are not fully understood, and pregnancy rates are relatively low. In view of the recent availability of pure recombinant human follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and improved clinical understanding of the use of gonadotropins in anovulatory disorders, the role of clomiphene citrate might need to be reevaluated. Method(s): Review of the recent literature on clomiphene citrate. Result(s): The final pharmacologic effects of clomiphene citrate depend on many variables. Its pharmacokinetics are largely unknown. The teratogenic effects seen in animals have not been observed in humans, but systematic studies have hardly been performed. The therapeutic effect of clomiphene citrate in anovulatory patients seems to be related to the increase of circulating gonadotropins, especially FSH. Results of low-dose gonadotropin schemes are at least similar to those of clomiphene citrate treatment. Conclusion(s): From a pharmacologic point of view, it is easier to achieve a temporary increase in FSH levels by administering recombinant FSH. In view of this, the use of clomiphene citrate might soon be an anachronism.
