8231. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 28491237
T1  - Syndrome X: Pathogenesis, clinical and therapeutic aspects
A1  - Williams K.V.
A1  - Korytkowski M.T. 
Y1  - 1998//
N2  - The syndrome of insulin resistance, also referred to as Syndrome X, links hyperinsulinemia, disordered glucose tolerance, dyslipidemia, and hypertension with risk for Type II diabetes mellitus and cardiovascular disease. Disordered hemostasis, central adiposity, and hyperuricemia are components now included in the description of this syndrome. In young women of perimenarchal age, insulin resistance is implicated in the pathogenesis of polycystic ovary syndrome, a disorder characterized by menstrual irregularity and androgen excess. Syndrome X is a highly prevalent disorder with both genetic and environmental factors being implicated in its pathogenesis. Excess caloric intake in combination with a sedentary life-style promote the phenotypic expression of this syndrome in genetically predisposed individuals. While the specific genetic defects are not identified, abnormalities of insulin signaling in insulin-sensitive tissues are described in individuals with manifestations of this syndrome. These signaling defects manifest as abnormalities in glucose disposal, free fatty acid metabolism, and glucose production. Early identification of individuals with evidence of insulin resistance is essential in order to forestall the more adverse clinical conditions associated with this disorder. Although there are no recommended methods for measuring insulin sensitivity outside research trials, identification can be relatively straightforward with careful physical examination that includes measurement of body mass index, waist circumference, and blood pressure, with laboratory assessment of fasting glucose and lipids. Early intervention with a low fat, high fiber diet in combination with regular aerobic exercise is effective in promoting weight reduction (when indicated), preventing weight gain, and reducing the risk for developing overt diabetes or cardiovascular disease. When nonpharmacologic therapy is ineffective alone, specific pharmacologic interventions that address individual components of Syndrome X are discussed.
