8291. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 26186922
T1  - Endometriosis and infertility
A1  - Prentice A.
A1  - Ingamells S. 
Y1  - 1996//
N2  - A causal relationship between infertility and endometriosis has been assumed from epidemiological studies which have shown an increased prevalence of endometriosis in infertile women. This relationship is obvious in women with endometriosis where structural damage to the tubes and ovaries is present. However, in women with no structural damage the causal relationship between endometriosis and infertility is less clear. Current evidence fails to provide proof of a causal relationship between mild endometriosis and infertility as the presence of the disease has not been shown to decrease fertility nor has treatment been shown to increase fertility. In addition, no convincing aetiological basis has been found to support the association between mild endometriosis and infertility. The aetiology of infertility in mild endometriosis has been extensively researched, with the occurrence of abnormalities at each stage of the female reproductive system being proposed. These abnormalities include defective folliculogenesis, anovulation, hyperprolactinaemia, luteinized unruptured follicle syndrome and luteal phase defects. Other factors thought to lead to infertility in mild endometriosis include an autoimmune response resulting in implantation failure, alterations in the peritoneal fluid with inflammatory changes and an increased spontaneous abortion rate. In addition, genetic studies on families affected by endometriosis have suggested a genetic component with a higher incidence of endometriosis in twins and first degree relatives. The evidence currently available fails to support a causal relationship between any of these factors and endometriosis. In the absence of a convincing aetiological basis of infertility in mild endometriosis and with no evidence to support an improvement in fertility following treatment of endometriosis, it must be concluded that there is no causal relationship. In these women active treatment of endometriosis should only be commenced if patients are symptomatic or have a deterioration in the disease.
