8305. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 26060227
ID  - 8635303 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8635303]
T1  - The application of transvaginal ultrasound for ovulation induction and in vitro fertilization
A1  - Nachtigall M.J.
A1  - Schwartz L.B. 
Y1  - 1996//
N2  - We are experiencing the vast technological advances that have allowed the application of TVUS to facilitate the diagnostic and therapeutic processes involved with ovulation induction and IVF-ET. In this way, IVF-ET has more recently been able to be performed in a less invasive, more accurate, and less costly manner for the patient. Although initially promising, the application of color Doppler flow monitoring has been disappointing in terms of significantly improving utero-ovarian monitoring during ovulation induction cycles and predicting pregnancy outcome. Results from the various centers have been inconsistent. Hopefully, future work will be aimed at improving standardization and reproducibility of Doppler parameters so that the value of this technique can be more objectively evaluated and applied. Transvaginal ultrasound in combination with transcervical instillation of sterile saline (sonohysterography) can provide detailed evaluation of the endometrial contour. When applied to the infertile patient, this technique has the potential to provide information previously only obtainable with hysterosalpingography but without the need for patient exposure to ionizing radiation. The application of sonohysterography to the work-up of the infertile patient before ovulation induction or for IVF-ET patients with implantation failure despite good fertilization outcome and embryo quality is a worthy area for future investigation. Finally, preliminary data suggest that three-dimensional US may become a valuable clinical tool and adjunct to two-dimensional US. Two-dimensional US images can sometimes be confusing and difficult to interpret. Three-dimensional US can facilitate diagnoses by allowing delineation of normal and abnormal structures in previously unobtainable planes. Three-dimensional imaging makes US easier to perform and interpret by providing a 'ready made' spatially oriented display of image position, which can be done by two-dimensional imaging only through interpretation of individual images and integration of these results by the clinician. Hopefully, future work will evaluate the application of three- dimensional imaging to the monitoring of ovulation induction cycles and IVF- ET procedures including oocyte retrieval and embryo transfer. Theoretically, more accurate follicular sizes and locations can be obtained by three- dimensional than two dimensional imaging when there are multiple follicles superimposed on each other. In addition, perhaps more can be learned about endometrial parameters with this new technique.
