8318. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 26143410
T1  - Pulsatile gonadotropin-releasing hormone is effective in treating women with anovulatory sterility
A1  - Falsetti L. 
Y1  - 1996//
N2  - From 1984 to 1991, 94 women, ages 24 to 33, with endocrinopathic sterility for at least 2 years were treated with pulsatile gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH), infused intravenously through Zyklomat pumps. Doses ranged from 1.8 to 5 mug/pulse every 90 minutes. Twenty-three patients had hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (HH), 41 had hypothalamic amenorrhea (HA), and 30 had polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Treatment with GnRH induced 182 cycles, resulting in 151 ovulatory cycles (83%), 45 term pregnancies (24.7%) (of which 6 were twin pregnancies [6.3%]), and 29 miscarriages (15.9%). In the 23 patients with HH, 60 cycles were induced; 55 were ovulatory (91.6%), resulting in 17 term pregnancies (28.3%) and 4 abortions (6.6%). In the 41 patients with HA, 66 cycles were induced; 60 (91%) were ovulatory, resulting in 18 term pregnancies (27.3%) (of which 4 were twin pregnancies [9.7%]) and 11 miscarriages (16.6%). Finally, in the 30 patients with PCOS, 56 cycles were induced, 36 of which were ovulatory (64%), resulting in 10 term pregnancies (17.9%) (2 of which were twin pregnancies [6.6%]) and 14 abortions (25%). Our data show that pulsatile GnRH is most effective in treating women with HH and HA and somewhat less so in women with PCOS. Incidence of side effects and complications was low.
