8367. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 25204887
T1  - Laparoscopic approaches to ovulation induction: An analysis of published data
A1  - Fox R.
A1  - Bhal P.
A1  - James M. 
Y1  - 1995//
N2  - Four laparoscopic techniques have been described (multiple ovarian biopsy, electrodiathermy, laser surgery, and cryocautery). Overall, 86% of women ovulate shortly after the procedure and of those who do not respond immediately, 68% then respond to clomiphene citrate. Two-thirds of the women conceive, and the miscarriage (15%) and multiple pregnancy (2%) rates are identical to those for normal women conceiving spontaneously. No major intra-operative complications have been described but peri-ovarian adhesions are common. Ovarian atrophy has followed laparoscopic electrodiathermy. All the methods appear to be of similar efficacy but multiple punch biopsy appears to have the advantages of being highly effective, simple to perform and relatively uncomplicated. Laparoscopic methods of inducing ovulation are the treatment of choice for women with polycystic ovarian disease (PCOD) who fail to respond to clomiphene citrate and in whom laparoscopy is not contraindicated. Future research should aim to determine morbidity rates for each surgical technique and the efficacy and safety of transvaginal ovarian needle puncture.
