T1  - Post-partum anovulation in nursing mothers
A1  - Taylor H.W.
A1  - Smith R.E.
A1  - Samuels S.J. 
Y1  - 1991//
N2  - An analysis of breastfeeding and ovulation data from 72 nursing mothers is presented. A proportional hazards model of the data strengthens the hypothesis that a pattern of short, frequent bouts of nursing defines a risk-set of women less susceptible to post-partum ovulation than those who choose to nurse on a schedule of relatively lengthy and infrequent bouts. In contrast, no effect of maternal weight-for-height on the month-specific rate of post-partum ovulation could be detected in the study population comprised of American mothers trained in self-observation of fertility signs.
