8502. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 20294427
T1  - The physiological basis of Superovulation
A1  - Armstrong D.T.
A1  - Leung P.C.K. 
Y1  - 1990//
N2  - Superovulation, a technique normally involving treatment with exogenous gonadotropic hormones, is now widespread in animal breeding programs aimed at increasing the number of oocytes ovulated in a given estrous cycle. Superovulation is characteristically undertaken in various livestock species, in conjunction with embryo transfer techniques, as a means of increasing the number of offspring of an individual female above that which she would be capable of producing in her lifetime by natural breeding. The offspring are usually of superior genetic merit or economic value. The same physiologic principles that lead to an increased ovulation rate in animals are now applied extensively in the treatment of infertility in women. Thus, by increasing the number of ova shed in anovulatory women, the probability of achieving pregnancy is increased. When applied as ovarian hyperstimulation treatments in human in vitro fertilization (IVF) or gamete intrafallopian transfer (GIFT) programs, multiple follicular development is induced, thus increasing the number of follicular oocytes available for collection by various aspiration techniques. Again, the probability of success is increased in proportion to the number of oocytes retrieved. Superovulation was first described by Smith and Engle1 after intramuscular implantation of anterior pituitary tissues in mice and rats. They recovered more than 60 ova from the fallopian tubes, or approximately 4 to 5 times the normal ovulation rate in these species. Soon after this pioneer work, Cole and Hart2 demonstrated the ability of the serum of pregnant mares to cause superovulation in immature rats, establishing the basis for what has been until recently the most widely used method of superovulation in farm livestock species. Much subsequent research has led to identification of the active ingredient in pregnant mare's serum as a glycoprotein hormone, equine chorionic gonadotropin (eCG), still often called pregnant mare serum gonadotropin (PMSG), or simply pregnant mare serum (PMS). This single protein hormone possesses biological activities similar to those of the two separate pituitary gonadotropic hormones, follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH). Equine chorionic gonadotropin and pituitary gonadotropin preparations of varying degrees of purity isolated from either animal pituitary tissue or postmenopausal human urine are now in widespread use for superovulation of domestic and exotic animal species, for treatment of human infertility, and for numerous research applications involving laboratory animals.
