8512. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 21078380
T1  - Polycystic ovarian disease
A1  - Wakim N.G. 
Y1  - 1990//
N2  - Polycystic ovaries are a sign and not a disease. They are common in prepubertal children, during puberty, and in adulthood. Polycystic ovarian disease (PCOD) is essentially a diagnosis arrived at by exclusion. The etiology of PCOD is not well understood; it could be due to a hypothalamic or an ovarian developmental arrest. The development of PCOD has been traced with the help of case studies of delayed puberty treated with gonadotropin-releasing hormone. There are endocrine aberrations associated with this disease, such as elevated free testosterone levels and a high luteinizing hormone to follicle- stimulating hormone ratio. The clinical presentation-irregular menses, infertility, obesity, hirsutism-is the most reliable in making the diagnosis. Treatment is determined by the needs of the patient.
