8520. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 19063225
ID  - 2692880 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2692880]
T1  - The statistical analysis of pulsatile hormone secretion data
A1  - Royston J.P. 
Y1  - 1989//
N2  - Knobil (1980) first demonstrated that the pulsatile nature of the secretion of gonadotrophin releasing hormone (GnRH), and hence of luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle stimulating hormone (FSH), was vital for the induction of menarche and ovulation. The main clinical applications of this principle are surveyed in Clayton (1987); they include the treatment of certain types of anovulation and of the absence of puberty and spermatogenesis. As a result of the growing awareness of the importance of pulsatility, there has been a substantial increase in the measurement and interpretation of patterns of pulsatile hormone secretion in serial blood samples, and the number of published papers in the field has risen sharply since 1982. However, it is evident from reading recent papers that there is no consensus as to which mathematical methods are best used to analyse the large numbers of hormone series thus collected. Presumably because of its physiological and clinical significance, LH is the hormone most frequently analysed in the literature. This review will implicitly concentrate on LH series, though some comments will be made on growth hormone (GH) pulsatility in the light of its relation with the growth rate (height velocity) of children (Hindmarsh et al. 1987). Other hormones whose pulsatile nature has been studied include FSH, oestradiol, progesterone, ACTH, prolactin and thyroid stimulating hormone. In this brief review, important issues in the analysis of pulsatile data and the major methods that have emerged since 1970 will be considered. An extensive bibliography will not be given because the intention is more to examine the methodology than to synthesize the results of many studies. For a much wider-ranging and detailed survey of the issues involved in peak detection, together with a useful description and comparison of most of the major computer algorithms, the reader is referred to Urban et al. (1988a).
