AN  - 10079700
ID  - 7421230 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7421230]
T1  - The effect of clomid and other triphenylethylene derivatives during pregnancy and the neonatal period
A1  - Clark J.H.
A1  - McCormack S.A. 
Y1  - 1980//
N2  - Clomid, Tamoxifen and Nafoxidine are triphenylethylene derivatives which act as estrogen agonists and/or antagonists. When these drugs are injected during the neonatal period of the rat they cause extensive estrogenic stimulation of the uterine epithelium. The stimulatory effect of these drugs on the epithelium appears to be a cell specific one since minimal stimulation of the stroma or myometrium was observed. A single injection of either Clomid or Nafoxidine during the neonatal period causes multiple abnormalities of the reproductive tract of the adult female rat. These abnormalities include cystic ovaries, ovarian hypoplasia, oviductal and uterine hyperplasia, pyometria, uterine metaplasia, uterine cystic hyperplasia and tumors of the uterus. Likewise, a single injection of Clomid during pregnancy (day 5 and 12) caused similar abnormalities to develop in both the offspring and the mothers. Nafoxidine treatment in the neonate results in nuclear accumulation and long-term retention of the estrogen receptor similar to that which has been observed in immature and adult rats. Therefore, we conclude that the abnormalities which we have observed are due to the long-term estrogenic effects of these drugs. Although triphenylethylene derivatives are used clinically as anti-estrogens, it is clear from these results that these drugs can be powerful estrogens and may be potentially dangerous for human use.
