8595. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1980 to 1987>
AN  - 16000812
T1  - Contraception and birthspacing
A1  - Cleland J.
A1  - Rutstein S. 
Y1  - 1986//
N2  - An average of one-third of birth intervals in 28 developing countries are shorter than two years. Short intervals tend to be more common in Latin America than in Asia, and they are most common in the Middle East. In most countries, the first and second children born in the family are at greatest risk of an inadequate gap between them. The reasons for the differences in length of birth intervals among countries are related not only to contraceptive practice but also to traditional birthspacing mechanisms, namely, breastfeeding and postpartum abstinence. There appears to be substantial latent demand for the use of contraceptives for birthspacing. The majority of mothers who want another child do not want to conceive for at least 18 months following childbirth, and traditional birthspacing mechanisms do not extend that long in most countries. In 17 Latin American and Caribbean countries, there is suprisingly little differential in levels of contraceptive use between women who say they have had all the children they want and those who want to postpone the next birth - 48 percent compared with 38 percent. The disparity is wider in Asia and the Middle East, where the proportion of women who use contraceptives to space births is relatively low compared with the proportion who use them to limit births. Few women in African countries are using contraceptives for either purpose. Contraceptive use for spacing appears to have lengthened birth intervals in Latin America, but the evidence for Asia is not as conclusive. Although there is a negative association between contraceptive use and breastfeeding, results from a number of surveys indicate that postpartum contraceptive practice tends to be a response to the resumption of menstruation rather than a deliberate substitution of contraceptives for natural birthspacing mechanisms. Considerable variation among the countries in the length of postpartum abstinence and anovulation precludes any standardized policy toward the optimal timing of adoption of contraceptives.
