8614. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1980 to 1987>
AN  - 15224085
ID  - 6441662 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=6441662]
T1  - Complications of multiple gestation
A1  - Mueller-Heubach E. 
Y1  - 1984//
N2  - Multiple pregnancies are associated with very marked increases in maternal complications and perinatal morbidity and mortality. The rate of multiple pregnancies following induction of ovulation with current methods is unacceptably high. Therefore, the indications for induction of ovulation have to be strict, and methods to restore spontaneous ovulation should be explored first. For example, before induction of ovulation as treatment for anovulation associated with obesity is done, an attempt should be made to attain a normal body weight in order to ascertain whether spontaneous ovulation can be accomplished in this manner. The risks of multiple pregnancy and obesity are too high to warrant ovulation induction when less risky therapeutic approaches are available. Whenever induction of ovulation is planned, the couple should be thoroughly informed not only about the rate of multiple pregnancies but, most importantly, the many risks of multiple pregnancy. With current subspecialization, frequently the reproductive endocrinologist induces ovulation and shares in the elation of the previously infertile couple when pregnancy is diagnosed. If a multiple pregnancy is encountered, the patient is often referred to a maternal-fetal medicine specialist, who then has to manage this high-risk gestation, which frequently ends in premature labor and perinatal death or morbidity. Such a situation requires great emotional support for the couple, who are not only filled with sadness about an adverse pregnancy outcome but frequently feel guilty about having accomplished the pregnancy bu ovulation induction. If all fetuses survive, the care and financial support of multiple babies presents a formidable task which imposes considerable stress on the parents. Depression and rarely even suicide can ensue. Further research and the development of better methods of ovulation induction not associated with high multiple pregnancy rates are necessary.
