T1  - Severe ovarian hyperstimulation following follicular aspiration
A1  - Friedman C.I.
A1  - Schmidt G.E.
A1  - Chang F.E.
A1  - Kim M.H. 
Y1  - 1984//
N2  - Superovulation has been used in most in vitro fertilization programs to increase the likelihood of oocyte recovery, subsequent fertilization, and pregnancy during each cycle. The use of gonadotropins for induction of ovulation in anovulatory women not associated with an in vitro fertilization-embryo transfer program is complicated by multiple gestations as well as hyperstimulation. To avoid hyperstimulation and multiple gestations a range of serum or urinary estrogen concentrations has been established empirically in each institution, which allows human chorionic gonadotropin to be administered safely but with relative efficacy. Hyperstimulation has not commonly been previously reported in women undergoing follicular aspiration as part of an in vitro fertilization program, despite estrogen concentrations that exceed the 'safe range' established for induction of ovulation. Puncture and aspiration of the follicle is believed responsible for the avoidance of hyperstimulation. To our knowledge this is the first report of severe hyperstimulation following in vitro fertilization in which all visible follicles were aspirated.
