AN  - 12007151
ID  - 7131438 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7131438]
T1  - Heterotopic pregnancy as a result of induced ovulation. A report of two cases
A1  - Koroly M.V.
A1  - Belsky D.H. 
Y1  - 1982//
N2  - Heterotopic, or combined intrauterine and extrauterine pregnancies are rare, but a significant number have been reported over the years. Duverney first described this condition in 1708 on a case observed at autopsy. In 1873 Gutzweiler reported a series of 276 cases in the first major literature review. Historically, the outcome of heterotopic pregnancy has been dependent on the technology available for diagnosis and treatment. Several cases of heterotopic pregnancy at term have been reported in which the extrauterine infant was delivered by laparotomy. Clomiphene citrate is indicated when infertility is a result of anovulation or oligoovulation. While the incidence of triplets and quadruplets is not markedly increased with clomiphene, there has been recent evidence of an increased incidence of twin gestations when the drug is used for induction of ovulation. Clomiphene has also been implicated in cases of torsed ovaries, theca lutein cysts and markedly enlarged ovaries. This paper reports 2 cases in which combined intrauterine and extrauterine pregnancy occurred in patients who had been treated with clomiphene for the induction of ovulation.
