T1  - Factors for resistance and ovarian hyperstimulation during therapy with menotropins
A1  - Haning Jr. R.V.
A1  - Shapiro S.S.
A1  - Carlson I.H. 
Y1  - 1981//
N2  - Factors for resistance to menotropins and hyperstimulation with menotropins were evaluated in women undergoing treatment for infertility. The dose of menotropins (AMPS) necessary for ovulation was found to be correlated with weight (WT), .65 and plasma prolactin (PRL), .46. PRL was also correlated with urinary estriol glucuronide (E3G), .52 and plasma estradiol (E2), .45. Although progesterone (P), 17-hydroxy-progesterone (17-P), androstenedione (DELTA4A), testosterone (T), testosterone free index (TFI), and dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) were evaluated as possible resistance factors, there was no evidence that any steroid hormone produced resistance to menotropin treatment. The concentration of plasma FSH required for progressive follicular development was similar in subjects with hypothalamic amenorrhea (HA) or polycystic ovarian disease (PCOD). In patients with PCOD failing to have progressive follicular development, FSH was slightly low although LH was higher than in responding subjects with HA. In 1 subject with acceptable pre-ovulatory E2 and subsquent hyperstimulation in 2 cycles, FSH was demonstrated to be markedly elevated, and LH was lower than in controls. With high levels of FSH and low levels of LH, hyperstimulation may occur at relatively low levels of plasma and urinary estrogen.
