8680. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1980 to 1987>
AN  - 11014010
ID  - 6793292 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=6793292]
T1  - Nutrition, fatness, puberty, and fertility
A1  - Frisch R.E. 
Y1  - 1981//
N2  - While the reproductive system is slowly maturing, the growing body also changes, not only in size and proportions, but in the relative proportions of the tissues, nerves, bone, muscle, and fat. The role of estrogen in modulating food intake, and fat storage during growth and maturation, and the reverse relationship indicated above, the importance of a particular fat/lean ratio, on estrogen secretion and metabolism have not yet been clarified. Adipose tissue itself may be a determinant of menarche and mature reproductive ability: through the conversion of androgens to estrogen, a critical amount of estrogen may be necessary to prime the ovary; body weight, hence fatness, influences the direction of estrogen metabolism to the most potent or least potent forms. Extreme leanness may be related to the production of anti-estrogens, the catechol estrogens; changes in body fat composition are correlated with changes in sex hormone binding globulin, thus regulating the availability of estradiol to the brain and other target tissues. Clinically, the minimal weight for height findings are useful in cases of nutritional amenorrhea. Knuth et al. point out that 'dietary treatment of patients with amenorrhea and loss of weight may replace gonadotropin therapy for induction of ovulation in a significant proportion of patients with anovulatory infertility'. With increasing numbers of serious women athletes and dancers, clinicians must also add to the list of possible causes of delayed menarche and amenorrhea, regular, intense, exercises which may be accompanied by the eating of bizarre foods. The effects of undernutrition and exercise on menarche and the menstrual cycle are apparently reversible. In some subjects a one or two kg weight change will turn cycles on and off. However, nothing is known as yet about the mechanisms involved, or about the long term effects on fertility. Finally, reports of height and weight data of undernourished or exercising women should include some index of the relationship of the individual heights and weights, such as percent ideal weight, or estimated total water as percent of body weight (even if the latter underestimates the lean mass for athletic women), in order to get some idea of the relative leanness of the women in relation to the normal standards. When the mean heights and weights are reported separately as in a study correlating the incidence of secondary amenorrhea with weekly training mileage, we do not know the variation in leanness of the individual athletes. In general, endocrinologic and metabolic data would be more meaningful if the height and weight, and age of menarche, were routinely reported.
