T1  - Pathophysiology of anovulation
A1  - Lasley B.L.
A1  - Judd H.L. 
Y1  - 1978//
N2  - The original hypothesis that a defective pituitary would elicit an abnormal response whereas a hypothalamic defect would not greatly alter the normal response has not been supported. Although occasionally helpful, in most instances the gonadotropin response to a single challenge of gonadotropin releasing factor is not in itself sufficient evidence to separate hypothalamic from pituitary defects. Diminished responses may be the result of chronic lack of hypothalamic stimulation of the pituitary, whereas normal pituitary responses have been demonstrated in patients with known pituitary disease. More recent studies employing smaller and/or repetitive stimulation of the gonadotropic cells in combination with steroid feedback maneuvers, which change the functional hypothalamic input, still hold promise in the future.
