T1  - Dermatoglyphical studies in Stein-Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Nagaonkar J.L. 
Y1  - 1978//
N2  - The genetic basis of abnormal steroidogenesis as reflected in dermal patterns was evaluated in 23 surgically verified Stein-Leventhal (S.L.) cases which showed peculiar features between those of Turner's syndrome. Klinefelter's syndrome and Superfemale. The main features were as follows: Total ridge count (T.R.C.) varied from 257 to 22. Sydney line was seen in eleven cases. Loops with more T.R.C. were more frequent. Atd angle was more than 48 in 4 cases. t' Was seen in 3 and t'' in 4 cases. a-b Distance was more than 30 in all cases. S hypothenar pattern was seen in 2 cases while oblique or transverse loop was seen in 7 cases. Y pattern not so far described was seen on base of great toe in one case. On soles- Distal loop was seen in 14 and arch in 2 cases. The majority of the cases with obesity and hirsutism showed androgenic preponderance with peculiar dermal patterns resembling males or Turner's syndrome while patients with oestrogenic preponderance showed patterns as in Klinefelter's syndrome or superfemale. This study strongly suggests a genetic abnormality in steroidogenesis as reflected in the dermal patterns and forms a bed-side diagnostic tool in suspected cases of Stein-Leventhal syndrome.
