A1  - Ferenczy A. 
Y1  - 1977//
N2  - The ultrastructural surface features of normal endometrium at various stages of the menstrual cycle were examined and compared with hyperplastic and neoplastic endometria using a scanning electron microscope. The endometrial surface characteristics were evaluated and correlated in relation to function and hormonal stimuli. In normal preovulatory surface epithelium 17beta estradiol stimulates the formation and development of a large number of cilia and microvilli. In sharp contrast to the glandular epithelium, the latter remain relatively unchanged during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle. This morphologic discrepancy between the surface and glandular epithelium indicates possibly a dissimilar response to cyclic hormonal stimuli and probably a reflection of different cellular functions. Secretion in the uterine lining epithelium is scant and constant throughout the cycle with a peak of apocrine secretion occurring at about the time of ovum implantation. This coincides with the postovulatory rise of progesterone. In hormonally unstimulated postmenopausal endometria, surface and cellular specializations such as cilia, microvilli and secretory activity are profoundly decreased or absent. In hyperplastic endometrium, ciliated cells and surface microvilli are considerably more numerous than in normal and anovulatory persistent proliferative endometrium. This is in keeping with exaggerated estrogenic stimulation. The morphologic effects of pharmacologic doses of synthetic progestins on hyperplastic and well-differentiated neoplastic endometria include secretory conversion, a decrease in the length of microvilli and loss of cilia. These features support the concept that while 17beta estradiol stimulates the growth of cilia and microvilli, progestagens promote secretory conversion and inhibit the development of estrogen-primed surface specializations. Unlike the cilia and microvilli in normal and hyperplastic endometria, they are comparatively reduced in well-differentiated adenocarcinoma. Ciliated cells are absent in neoplasms of lesser differentiation. The failure to express estrogen-influenced cellular characteristics in high grade endometrial neoplasms seems to be related to neoplastic dedifferentiation and to be independent of the 17beta estradiol cytoplasmic receptor content.
