T1  - Bilateral ovarian cysts in early infancy
A1  - Alvear D.T.
A1  - Rayfield M.M. 
Y1  - 1976//
N2  - 71 cases of ovarian cysts in infancy have been described previously in the English literature. 3 cases were bilateral. This report describes a case of multiocular follicular cysts involving both ovaries in early infancy. Small follicular cysts occur normally in infants and children as a manifestation of nonovulatory follicular ripening and spontaneous involution that occurs throughout premenstrual life. Only rarely do these follicular cysts attain large size and present as surgical problems. The exact etiology of these masses is unknown, but a disturbance of the ovarian anterior pituitary axis is postulated. Experimentally, high doses of gonadotropin have produced cystic hyperplasia in animals. Decrease in urinary estriol in this patient's mother at 32 wk gestation, leading to early termination of pregnancy, could have contributed to the development of the polycystic reaction of both ovaries in response to hormonal imbalance. Polyhydramnios is seen in 5-10% of these mothers. Lutein cysts are frequently seen in infants of diabetic mothers. The most common complications of untreated ovarian cysts are torsion, hemorrhage into the cyst or into the abdominal cavity, rupture of the cyst, and infarction or necrosis of the cyst.
