8738. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 8000295
ID  - 1009732 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1009732]
T1  - Disturbance in the negative feedback loops of the pituitary ovarian axis
A1  - Baird D.T. 
Y1  - 1976//
N2  - In this chapter I have illustrated how the production of hormones ectopic to the pituitary ovarian axis may disrupt the normal regulatory feedback mechanisms. Although it is well recognised that gross disorders of the thyroid and adrenal result in alteration in pituitary ovarian function, our knowledge of the normal interrelationship between these glands is scanty. For example, the factors which determine the increased secretion of androgens from the adrenal glands at puberty and importance of the adrenal in determining the change in hypothalamic sensitivity which occurs at this time, are unknown. It has been suggested that prolactin may increase the amount of androgen secreted by the adrenal in response to stimulation by ACTH. It is possible therefore that prolactin influences the pituitary ovarian axis by regulating the secretion of adrenal androgens, as well as by its effects on the hypothalamus and ovary. A possible mechanism by which the thyroid and other hormones might affect the pituitary ovarian axis is by influencing the metabolism of ovarian steroids. In hyperthyroidism, for example, relatively more estradiol is metabolised to 2 methoxy estrone rather than to estriol. I have suggested that excess extraglandular production of estrone from androstenedione may play a key role in determining the abnormalities in secretion of gonadotropin in the polycystic ovarian syndrome. However, apart from the fact that there is a correlation between the overall rate of conversion and age and body weight, very little is known about the factors which determine rates of aromatisation in individual tissues and the extent to which estrogen produced in these tissues re enters the blood. If androgens play a role in modulating the feedback effects of estrogens in the normal female, the rate of aromatisation of androgens by the hypothalamic nuclei responsible for the control of gonadotropin secretion may determine the magnitude of the effect. As our knowledge of these factors influencing the HPO axis expands, it may be possible to explain some of the abnormalities in ovarian function which present clinically as minor alterations in the pattern of menstruation, e.g. short luteal phase, premenstrual tension, etc.
