8748. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 7147954
ID  - 1095259 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1095259]
T1  - Dynamics of hypothalamic pituitary function during puberty
A1  - Schoenberg D.K. 
Y1  - 1975//
N2  - The results of animal experiments and physiological and clinical data in children may be summarised for the following events and mechanisms of puberty onset (Figure 7). Prepubertally a highly sensitive negative feedback of gonadal and non gonadal sex steroids in the regulation of gonadotropin secretion is operative. The hypothalamic inhibitory site may be situated in the amygdala, possibly in the anterior hypothalamic area and/or the median eminence. Maturation of the amygdala and/or a rise in threshold to sex steroids in the median eminence during late prepuberty may then elicit increased gonadotropin secretion, especially FSH. Increased circulating levels of oestrogen then influence the anterior hypothalamic and preoptic area to induce cyclic influences on the median eminence for the secretion of gonadotropins in females. Increased secretion of LH RH may be assumed from the increased responsiveness of the pituitary to exogenous LH RH in the late prepubertal period. At this time an increased sleep pattern, especially of LH, becomes evident. At onset of puberty the sleep associated episodic secretion of LH becomes more marked and the threshold for the negative feedback of sex steroids on gonadotropin regulation rises further. In the rat prolactin levels rise steeply preventing a further increase in gonadotropin secretion. In girls the reactivity to LH RH changes; the response of FSH is less marked, starting from elevated base levels, while the response of LH to LH RH becomes more impressive. During late puberty the mechanism of positive feedback especially of oestrogens to LH secretion develops. After a period of anovulatory menstruation, ovulation becomes regular and spermatogenesis starts in the male. Although a great deal of information has accumulated the exact mechanism, especially of timing of onset of puberty so closely related to bone age and bodily development, remains obscure. Ageing of regulatory structures, perhaps under timing influences such as light, may alter cerebral responsiveness to negative and positive feedback.
