T1  - Serum androstenedione levels during normal and human menopausal gonadotropin induced human pregnancies
A1  - Thorneycroft I.H.
A1  - Barberia J.M.
A1  - Ribeiro W.O.
A1  - Mishell Jr. D.R. 
Y1  - 1975//
N2  - 17 Hydroxyprogesterone (17 OHP) and androstenedione (A) were measured frequently during the first trimester of 5 human pregnancies. Two were normally conceived and 3 were human menopausal gonodotrophin (HMG) induced. Of the HMG induced, 2 showed signs of hyperstimulation and one did not. 17 OHP and A patterns were very similar in the HMG induced pregnancies from about days 25 to 60, after which the 17 OHP levels continued to drop. The A remained fairly constant after that time. In the normally conceived pregnancies the 17 OHP showed its characteristic rise and fall from about days 25 to 60, but A remained relatively constant throughout this period of time. The pattern of A in normal pregnancies is in marked contrast to that observed in HMG induced pregnancies. Results from HMG induced pregnancies may not, therefore, be always applicable to normal ones.
