8753. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 5212252
ID  - 1057407 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1057407]
T1  - Focal nodular hyperplasia of the liver: a further contribution
A1  - O'Reilly K. 
Y1  - 1975//
N2  - A new dimension has been added to the concept of focal nodular hyperplasia of the liver, in the observation of recent upsurge in incidence pari passu with the use of anovulatory pills. A newly recognized significant surgical feature of the disease is its propensity to serious haemorrhage. There is a benign entity of the liver that is characterized by the presence of a nodule, usually solitary, usually situated immediately under the capsule, usually tan in colour, usually without a true capsule, and usually with a depressed central eschar. It is composed of normal hepatocytes, formed into pseudo lobules by fibrous tissue tracts in which proliferating ducts and lymphocytes are evident and in which there is evidence of vascular proliferation. Surgical awareness of this relatively new and seemingly increasingly reported condition of focal nodular hyperplasia of the liver is important not only because it may simulate malignancy at laparotomy, but also because it can present as abdominal pain or as an abdominal mass, or as abdominal haemorrhage. Simple limited excisional therapy is adequate therapy for the lesion discovered as a coincidence in the course of a laparotomy, but very much more heroic surgery would seem to be required for the more catastrophic presentations of the lesion. Mays (1974) suggested that a probable basis for the occurrence of the hyperplastic nodule is a localized intrahepatic thrombotic event. It is probable that the lesions undergo retrogression with the cessation of the pill. Certainly the reported cases would indicate that prolonged exposure to the pill is significant in the development of the lesion and in its clinical obtrusion. It is tentatively postulated that the continued taking of the anovulatory pill, once the lesion has formed, induces a friable vascularity which accounts for the apoplectic episodes. It is reasoned that the hormones of pregnancy have a vascularizing effect on tissues undergoing reparation, and it is thought that the same effect may stem from the situation of a pseudo pregnancy that anovulents induce.
