T1  - Hyperthecosis: an inheritable form of polycystic ovarian disease
A1  - Wilroy Jr. R.S.
A1  - Givens J.R.
A1  - Wiser W.L.
A1  - Coleman S.A.
A1  - Andersen R.N.
A1  - Summitt R.L. 
Y1  - 1975//
N2  - Familial hirsutism in females is frequently dismissed by clinicians as a nonpathologic entity. Several families were studied in whom multiple members are hirsute and have abnormal menses, oligomenorrhea or secondary amenorrhea. Some of these affected females have had polycystic ovaries, with or without hyperthecosis. Hyperthecosis is presently employed to designate polycystic ovaries with isolated nests of luteinized cells scattered throughout the stroma. Family studies of polycystic ovarian disease, hirsutism and oligomenorrhea have suggested dominant transmission, probably autosomal. Ovarian hyperthecosis has also been documented in several families. The etiology of polycystic ovarian disease including hyperthecosis is obscure. The manifestations are variable, not only in phenotypic expression of the affected patient but in ovarian morphology and biochemical parameters. The cyclic function of the ovary and alterations with age serve to compound the complex manifestations of these disorders.
