T1  - Post 'pill' amenorrhoea
A1  - Buttram Jr V.C.
A1  - Vanderheyden J.D.
A1  - Besch P.K.
A1  - Acosta A.A. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - Thirty nine patients with post 'pill' amenorrhea (amenorrhea persisting for at least six months after birth control drugs were discontinued) were evaluated by previous menstrual history, various laboratory assays, endoscopy, progesterone withdrawal menstruation, and various ovulatory stimulants. A review of 271 cases reported in the English literature since 1966 was combined with the authors' data in an effort to answer many questions regarding this syndrome. The female with a history of irregular menses appears more susceptible to developing postdrug amenorrhea. Galactorrhea in the post drug period is an ominous sign of hypothalamic pituitary ovarian axis hypersuppression. Laboratory data was not helpful in diagnosis, prognosis or therapy as compared to endoscopy or progesterone withdrawal tests. The latter appeared the most beneficial test. Various drugs (Clomid, corticoids, HCG, Pergonal plus HCG) were effective in inducing ovulation and subsequent conception in 50% of those patients desiring fertility.
