T1  - Psychosomatic aspects of induced ovulation
A1  - Hertz D.G.
A1  - Schneidman G. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - Preliminary observations were reported on emotional reactions of three women conceiving after long (3-7 yr) infertility. Short clinical vignettes described fluctuations of mood and increased emotional lability, during repeated therapeutic efforts to induce ovulation. It is assumed that ovulation inducing drugs create emotional manifestations similar to those occurring in normal adolescence. The sudden confrontation of the anovulatory woman with her reproductive ability provokes this normative crisis. Multiple intrapsychic and interpersonal factors (parental relationship, husband role, feminine identity) are considered as precipitating factors in the development. Duration of the sterile period appears to be of major importance to the extent and quality of the emotional reactions.
