A1  - Danowski T.S. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - Portions of ovaries obtained from 22 women with morbid obesity exhibited a statistically significant greater frequency of hyalinized capsules, luteinized atretic follicles, and atypical maturing follicles, but fewer normal maturing follicles, corporal lutea, and corpora albicantia than those from 20 control, nonobese women of comparable age. Cystic change was not prominent, distinguishing this constellation of findings from those observed in the so called polycystic ovarian syndrome. The histopathologic changes are consonant with the decrease of serum FSH and increase in LH noted in some of these women. Although the mechanism responsible for these ovarian changes is as yet inapparent, the findings strongly suggest that extremely obese women may be predisposed to premature ovarian failure.
