AN  - 5022144
ID  - 4823512 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=4823512]
T1  - Neonatal intrahypothalamic androgen administration: the influence of dose and age on androgenization of female rats
A1  - Lobl R.T.
A1  - Gorski R.A. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - In order to investigate the relatively abrupt decline in the ability of androgen to induce permanent anovulatory sterility in adult females following subcutaneous injection after 5 days of age, moderate doses of testosterone propionate (TP) were implanted directly into various brain regions of female rats aged 7 to 20 days. Age at vaginal opening was noted as was ovarian morphology at 45 and 95 days of age. A high incidence of anovulatory sterility was observed in adult females following the implantation of a total of 60 mug at the level of the anterior commissure in the dorsal preoptic anterior hypothalamus as late as postnatal day 11. Implantation of lower doses of TP (30 mug, 10 mug) was less effective. Intrahypothalamic pellets of TP were significantly more effective in inducing sterility than the same amount administered systemically. Cortical implants were also effective, but implants of TP into the lateral amygdala were completely ineffective in producing sterility. Vaginal opening was markedly accelerated following implantation of 60 or 30 mug TP between 9 and 11 days of age. This response was blocked by simultaneous ovariectomy.
