T1  - An immunological factor in the etiology of human ovulatory failure
A1  - Mori T.
A1  - Kasai K.
A1  - Suzuki A.
A1  - Kitagawa M.
A1  - Nishimura T. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - In an attempt to elucidate the role of the immune mechanism in menopausal women, ovulatory failure, a total of 57 human subjects were examined using the indirect immunofluorescence technique. Ovaries and sera were obtained from patients with normal cycles, anovulatory cycles, granulosa cell tumors and chorionic tumors. In 19 of the 57 cases there was a positive reaction, and 16 of the patients were diagnosed as having idiopathic ovulatory failure on endocrinologic examination prior to surgery. Five different patterns of fluorescence were distinguished in the ovaries; fine striped, reticular, fine granular, patchy and lumpy patterns. The gross findings for the ovaries of the 16 patients with anti ovarian antibody were a polycystic ovary in 13 cases, a hypoplastic ovary in 2 cases, and an atrophic ovary in one case. Control studies with sera from women with normal cycles, normal adult men, normal pregnant women and normal children gave negative reactions. The direct immunofluorescent method with antihuman gamma globulin also gave negative results. Anti ovarian antibodies specifically present in the sera of patients with idiopathic anovulation indicate that an autoimmune mechanism participates as an etiologic factor in the development of idiopathic anovulation. (Journal received: Dec. 1975)
