8769. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 5083615
T1  - Causal relationships between endocrine metabolic variables in patients with endometrial carcinoma
A1  - Lucas W.E. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - From the clinical and laboratory data reviewed it is apparent that the evidence for a basic derangement of endocrine homeostasis in patients who develop endometrial carcinoma is largely circumstantial. The precise nature of this endocrinopathy, if it exists, is far from clear. At this point in time more pieces of the puzzle are missing than are in place. To assume that there is a single cause for endometrial carcinoma would be a gross oversimplification of the problem. For example, no reference has been made to evidence for and against the concept that ionizing radiation for benign or malignant disease may be associated with an increased incidence of endometrial carcinoma 10 to 20 or more years later. In addition, the question of viral oncogenesis remains unexplored relative to the endometrium. Endometrial epithelium can develop atypical proliferation under prolonged stimulation by estrogen unopposed by progesterone. Evidence has been reviewed which supports the concept that the obesity, impaired fertility and oligoovulatory states seen in many endometrial cancer patients are related to hypothalamic pituitary dysfunction leading to ovarian (and possibly adrenal) dysfunction. Although all attempts to date have been unsuccessful, it would be helpful to establish a subhuman primate model for study of endometrial carcinoma. The establishment of a cell line of endometrial carcinoma which has apparently retained its original histologic and biologic characteristics, recently reported by Kuramoto, offers an opportunity to study basic tumor cell biology and the effects of manipulation of the hormonal milieu in vitro. Finally, from the standpoint of endocrine treatment of endometrial carcinoma, the reports of Nordqvist regarding the in vitro potentiation of the antitumor effects of progestogens by estradiol are noteworthy, and deserve clinical exploration. It is important to know whether or not anaplastic metastatic or locally recurrent endometrial carcinoma, which is unresponsive to high dose progestogen therapy, might respond more favorably to pretreatment or concurrent treatment with estradiol.
