8770. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 5063678
T1  - Prolactin and human reproduction
A1  - McNeilly A.S. 
Y1  - 1974//
N2  - Prolactin appears to play an active role in human reproduction. No consistent pattern of prolactin secretion is seen during the menstrual cycle, and circulating levels are unrelated to changes in LH, FSH, oestrogen, or progesterone. Within the follicular fluid, however, prolactin levels change in relation to follicular development. It appears that basal levels of prolactin are essential for ovarian steroidogenesis. In contrast, elevated levels appear to inhibit steroidogenesis at the level of the ovary, resulting in failure of the normal positive feedback to LH and FSH secretion, anovulation, and amenorrhoea. During pregnancy maternal levels of prolactin rise gradually towards term. High levels of prolactin are found in amniotic fluid, and levels in the fetus at term are elevated and related to those found in the mother. On the maternal side prolactin probably forms part of the mammogenic complex, whereas the function of the fetal and amniotic fluid prolactin is unknown. During the puerperium prolactin levels are elevated due to suckling, and the initiation of milk secretion appears to depend on the removal of inhibition by fetoplacental steroids. A direct effect of prolactin on the ovary probably explains the anovulation that accompanies lactation. (31 references)
