8776. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 2 of 2
AN  - 4092133
ID  - 4200499 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=4200499]
T1  - Immunization of female baboons with hapten coupled gonadotropins
A1  - Stevens V.C. 
Y1  - 1973//
N2  - Adult female baboons (Papio anubis) were immunized with hapten coupled gonadotropin preparations of human, ovine, monkey and baboon origin. All animals produced antibodies to the immunizing antigens within 3 to 5 wk from first injection. IgM antibodies were relatively abundant only during the first 8 wk from first detection of antibodies. Cross reaction of antibodies to sulphanilazo human LH, HCG, and ovine LH with unaltered baboon LH was significant only during the period of IgM abundance. Antibodies against sulphanilazo monkey and baboon LH cross reacted with unaltered baboon LH as long as titers persisted. Effects of immunizations on the menstrual cycle were assessed by measurements of urinary estrogens, urinary LH and plasma progestins. Reduction of endogenous hormone secretion correlated with titers of cross reacting antibodies. Disruption of ovulation occurred for 2 to 3 mth with human and ovine gonadotropin immunizations but baboons receiving sulphanilazo monkey or baboon LH were anovulatory for 4 to 8 mth. These data provide evidence that hapten coupling produces structural changes in gonadotropin molecules that enhance their antigenicity and the cross reactivity of antibodies raised to them.
