AN  - 5054929
ID  - 4795133 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=4795133]
T1  - The treatment of secondary amenorrhoea with menopausal gonadotrophins
A1  - Brosens I.
A1  - Renaer M. 
Y1  - 1973//
N2  - Twenty six patients received human menopausal gonadotrophin (Humegon) in a 1-3-5 day regimen. The dose of Humegon was gradually increased in consecutive treatments according to resulting estrogen activity. Human chorionic gonadotrophin (Pregnyl) was administered as single injection of fixed dosage on the 9th day. Out of 16 patients treated for secondary amenorrhoea and infertility 10 became pregnant. There were 3 multiple pregnancies (2 twins, 1 septuplet) and 3 abortions (1 single, 1 twin, 1 septuplet). No case of clear hyperstimulation syndrome occurred. The total effective Humegon dose varied between 450 and 2,025 IU HMG (IRP 2). Total estrogen excretion on the 9th day of treatment, except for one case (septuplet), was below 300/mug/24 hrs. It is felt that this 1-3-5-9 regimen causes less hyperstimulation than the daily injection regimen and therefore constitutes an improvement.
