8787. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 2 of 2
AN  - 4197835
T1  - Turner group: Statistical survey and relations with the Stein Leventhal syndrome
A1  - Giordano A.
A1  - Lavezzi A.M.
A1  - Grimoldi M.G. 
Y1  - 1972//
N2  - The karyological analysis of 3000 women in Milan has revealed 6 cases of Turner syndrome. Two of them had a karyotype XO, three a mosaicism XX/XO/XXX and one a mosaicism XX/XX(qi)/XO. In two cases of X monosomy, one X had paternal origin and the other one derived from the mother, as confirmed by the Xg blood group. All the cases had increased levels of glucose 6 phosphate dehydrogenase in the serum; the significance of this finding is still under investigation. Levels of urinary 17 KS were normal in cases of complete Turner syndrome with XO karyotype, whereas they were significantly decreased in the cases with mosaicism and with isochromosome. A constant finding in 5 cases was a marked hypoplasia of the uterus and ovary. Audiological examination revealed in the first case, a slight bilateral perceptive deficit. No case of color blindness was observed. All the patients showed a distal location of the axial triradius and an increased number of the finger ridges of dermatoglyphs. Barr bodies were constantly absent in the complete cases of the syndrome while they were less constantly observed in the patients with mosaicism and in those with isochromosome. In the latter, 5% of oral mucosal cells presented Barr's bodies larger than normal. Three cases of Stein Leventhal syndrome were also observed: of these the first one showed an XX/XX(p-)/XXfr/XX(qi) mosaicism, while the others had a normal karyotype. The relationship between Turner group and Stein Leventhal syndrome is discussed with regard to the current literature. The finding of 'hyperostosis frontalis interna' in one case of the Turner group and in another one of Stein Leventhal syndrome is described, and the coincidence is underlined.
