8799. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281397546
ID  - 13483894 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=13483894]
T1  - Hyperthecosis of ovaries (adrenal hyperplasia) - Editorial
A1  - Anonymous.
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - At the weekly clinical pathological conference at the Massachusetts General Hospital, a 13-year-old school girl was presented. There was a history of rapid growth and development, weight gain to 325 lbs. There had been one menstrual cycle at the age of 11 and amenorrhoea since that time. Patient's hirsutism appeared 8 months before admission. There was no change in the character of the voice. Mental development was normal. The patient's mother was also obese and had had a bilateral oophorectomy in another hospital. On physical examination there was only slight enlargement of the clitoris. All parts of the body including arms and legs were proportionally obese. The blood sugar was within normal limits. The 17-ketosteroid excretion was 10 mg. in 24 hr. The 17-hydroxycorticosteroid excretion after ACTH was 43 mg. in 24 hr. (control: 12 mg. per 24 hr. ). The FSH excretion was 6.5 mouse U. Cytological examination showed 25% basal cells. The skull X-ray was normal. Retroperitoneal air injections showed slightly enlarged adrenal glands. At operation 2 greatly enlarged ovaries having the typical appearance of Stein-Leventhal ovaries were found. Wedge resection was done and histological study of the ovaries showed many large clear luteinized cells surrounded by spindle cells of ovarian stroma. The microscopical diagnosis was hyperthecosis of the ovaries.
