Y1  - 1956//
N2  - Pathological examination of ovaries from 740 unselected autopsied cases permitted the collection of 26 instances of bilateral polycystic change, including 2 children, 1 woman aged 75, and the remainder of child-bearing age. Histological examination included not only the ovaries but also the endometrium (hyperplasia of cystic or adenomatous type in 13 cases, normal secretory endometrium in 1 case and inactive endometrium in 10 cases), the breast (adenofibrosis or chronic cystic mastitis in 14 and 15 cases examined), the thyroid (9 abnormal glands among 25 glands examined), and the pituitary (all seven glands available showed increased proportions of basophils). No significant adrenal or pancreatic islet abnormalities were observed. Among 21 adult women, 8 were obese, 4 had diabetes mellitus, 2 had hirsutism and 1 had acne. Of 10 married women, 6 were sterile. The material represents a rather homogeneous group pathologically, characterized by the frequent simultaneous occurrence of pituitary basophilism, polycystic ovaries, and mammary fibrocystic disease. The lack of endometrial hyperplasia in 10 cases was perhaps due to the effects of the major disease present (pulmonary tb, cardiac disease, sepsis). Pituitary basophilism with an inferred FSH hypersecretion was considered responsible for the observed ovarian stromal hyperplasia and the formation of multiple follicle cysts, and secondarily responsible for the changes in the target organs of ovarian oestrogen.
