ID  - 14370485 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14370485]
T1  - Clinical vagaries of the Stein-Leventhal ovary
A1  - Fitzgerald J.A.
A1  - Crossley J.L. 
Y1  - 1955//
N2  - There is a marked variability in the clinical picture of the Stein-Leventhal syndrome. The original concept consisted of menstrual irregularity, primary amenorrhoea, sterility, masculine type hirsutism, retarded breast development and obesity, in the presence of an enlarged polycystic ovary. The Stein-Leventhal ovary has a tunica albuginea permeated with excessive amounts of collagen. The underlying stroma contains follicle cysts of varying size with hypertrophic granulosa cells and characteristically hyperplastic theca interna. The authors present the following clinical variations: menorrhagia, persistent and progressive dysmenorrhoea, relative infertility and no uniformity in the findings of mammary hyperplasia and hirsutism.
