T1  - Symptomatic hypoglycemia in adults: A protocol for clinical and laboratory evaluation
A1  - Crofford O.B.
A1  - Graber A.L. 
Y1  - 1973//
N2  - The procedure used in evaluating adults who present with symptoms suggesting hypoglycemia is outlined In most instances the hypoglycemia is not brought on by fasting but follows the ingestion of high carbohydrate foods. In these cases the assay of insulin in the serum is not required and the diagnosis can usually be confirmed by a 5 hour oral glucose tolerance test. On those rare occasions when hypoglycemia occurs when food is withheld, serum insulin assays are of definite value in making an accurate preoperative diagnosis of insulinoma and in avoiding abdominal exploration in patients who do not have a surgically treatable condition.
