8805. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 293069960
T1  - Radioimmunoassay of serum FSH and LH during the normal menstrual cycle and in anovulatory conditions
A1  - Minagawa J.
A1  - Aono T.
A1  - Kawamura K. 
Y1  - 1972//
N2  - Abnormality in the gonadotrophin secretion profile was studied in anovulatory conditions. The daily serum levels of FSH and LH were determined by the sensitive and specific double antibody radioimmunoassay in 7 women with normal menstrual cycles, one case of luteal insufficiency, 3 patients with anovulatory cycles and an anovulatory woman with oligomenorrhea. Determinations of FSH and LH were also made in 4 anovulatory women during their treatment cycles with clomiphene citrate. The FSH and LH levels during normal menstrual cycles were obtained in relation to the day of LH surge and averaged. The mean level of LH in the first half of the follicular phase (10.2 5.6 mIU/ml) increased towards the second half (20.0 5.6 mlU/ml). At midcycle, the abrupt surge of LH level (113.1 20.0 mIU/ml) was demonstrated. The value then decreased to a lower level (11.8 1.5 mlU/ml) throughout the luteal phase. The serum level of FSH stayed at a high level (5.9 0.3 mIU/ml) during the first two thirds of the follicular phase followed by the transitory drop (4.9+0.4 mIU/ml) in the last third of the follicular phase. The FSH pattern showed a peak (14.1 + 1.9 mIU/ml) which coincided with the LH surge, then decreased to a lower level (3.7+0.4 mIU/ml) in the early luteal phase, followed by a gradual increase towards the end of this phase. The mean ratios of LH to FSH in the follicular, ovulatory and luteal phases were 2.9, 8.0 and 3.2 respectively. The remarkable changes of profile in a case of luteal insufficiency were a relatively low peak of LH (45.6 mIU/ml) at midcycle and decreased LH/FSH ratio (12) in the follicular phase. The duration of high basal body temperature (B.B.T.) was 10 days. The peak levels of LH in 3 anovulatory cycles were found to be lower (28.3-37.0 mIU/ml) than the normal ovulatory peak. Two to five days rise in B.B.T. was observed following the LH peak until the onset of the next menstruation. The mean ratios of LH to FSH before the LH peak in all cases were low (1.1, 12 and 1.5). The serum levels of FSH and LH as well as the mean ratios of LH to FSH were constantly low during the first 30 days of the cycle in an anovulatory woman with oligomenorrhea. Clomiphene citrate induced ovulation in 2 out of 4 anovulatory patients. The apparent findings in ovulatory cases were the two peaks of both LH and FSH. The first small peak was found during medication and the second peak, comparable to the ovulatory peak, was demonstrated during 10 to 11 days after initiation of clorniphene therapy. The above patterns of both LH and FSH were not observed in anovulatory cases, only a moderate rise in LH level being noted. The decreased ratio of LH and FSH in the follicular phase and low or no LH peak at midcycle compared to the normal menstrual cycle were constant findings in the mild anovulatory cases. It seems that the presence of LH as well as FSH in the follicular phase is necessary for maturation of the follicle and subsequent ovulation.
