8807. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 293123548
T1  - Hormonal requirements of various strains of mouse mammary gland in organ culture
A1  - Vir Singh D. 
Y1  - 1972//
N2  - With the organ culture method, studies were made to analyze the strain differences in hormone responsiveness to mouse mammary glands. Two principal questions were asked: How many days of pretreatment in vivo are required to allow lobuloalveolar differentiation of mouse mammary gland in response to hormones in vitro? And: given the optimal duration of pretreatment, what is the minimal hormonal combination that will induce lobuloalveolar differentiation in vitro in mammary glands of mice of different strains? Four strains of mice were examined in regard to the hormonal requirements for induction of mammary gland lobuloalveolar differentiation in vitro. I(s) required 5 days of pretreatment with estradiol and progesterone to show development in vitro; C3H required 9 days; C57BL and A required 15 days. The greater length of pretreatment was correlated with the absence of inherited hormonal influence and the minimal hormonal requirements varied with different strains in vitro. The concentration of 0.1 mug aldosterone/ml of medium was adequate for all strains except A, which needed a higher concentration. Insulin requirement ranged from 0.5-2.5 mug/ml; prolactin and growth hormone requirements, from 0.25-5.0 mug/ml. These requirements in vitro and inherited hormonal influence were not correlated.
