8810. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 293120796
T1  - Aspects of physiological and pharmacological regulation of blood flow through retina and uvea. a study in cats and monkeys
A1  - Alm A. 
Y1  - 1972//
N2  - The effects of changes in intraocular pressure (IOP), arterial PO., arterial PCO2. and sympathetic tone, as well as the effects of some vasoactive drugs on blood flow through the various vascular beds of the eye and on oxygen supply to the retina have been studied in cats and monkeys. Blood flow through the choroid is very high. It is markedly increased by changes in the arterial PCO. and reduced by stimulation of the sympathetics. Increments in IOP result in blood flow reduction proportionate to the reductions in ocular perfusion pressure. If the flow reduction is moderate, the reduced blood flow is at least partly compensated by an increase in extraction of oxygen per volume blood, resulting in a largely unchanged total oxygen extraction. The different vascular beds of the anterior uvea seem to react similarly to various stimuli. The blood flow rates in the different parts are increased by cholinergic drugs, reduced by sympathetic stimulation and little affected by moderate increments in IOP. Flow through the retinal vessels is of the same order as that in white matter of the brain. Sympathetic stimulation seems to reduce blood flow through the innermost layers of the retina, but total retinal blood flow is not significantly changes. The lipid soluble drug papaverine caused marked increments in retinal oxygen tension, whilst various vasoactive drugs, that can be presumed to have difficulties in penetrating a lipid membrane, had no effects. Moderate increments in IOP did not reduce retinal oxygen tension or retinal blood flow. Average blood flow through the prelaminar part of the optic nerve, however, was reduced to about the same degree as blood flow through the choroid. This may be explained by the anatomy of the vascular supply to the optic nerve head; the prelaminar part of the optic nerve is supplied mainly by vessels from the peripapillary choroid. It is suggested that the susceptibility of the optic nerve head to increments in IOP is partly due to its lack of autoregulation of blood flow.
