8811. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 293126621
T1  - The relative roles of exogenous and endogenous follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) in human follicular maturation and ovulation induction
A1  - Berger M.J.
A1  - Taymor M.L.
A1  - Karam K.
A1  - Nudemberg F. 
Y1  - 1972//
N2  - In an attempt to elucidate the roles of follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) in the normal menstrual cycle and in patients with ovulatory defects, 8 subjects were treated alternately with pituitary FSH alone and human menopausal gonadotropin (HMG) which contained equal amounts of FSH and LH. In patients with gonadotropin deficient amenorrhea, FSH alone was incapable of producing full follicular maturation as determined by urinary and serum estrogen response, despite high peripheral levels of FSH. The addition of LH in the form of HMG produced a full follicular response with relatively lower peripheral FSH levels. In contrast, patients with polycystic ovarian disease and normal endogenous gonadotropin levels responded similarly to FSH alone and to HMG. In the latter group, adequate or exaggerated follicular maturation was produced with either preparation. These results confirm previous observations in animals that LH is either directly or indirectly essential for the maturation of the ovarian follicle. They also suggest that gonadotropin therapy would be best accomplished with gonadotropin preparations containing varying concentrations of LH.
