8816. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 292122662
T1  - Eflect of prenatal administration of testosterone on ovarian function in rate
A1  - Pels E.
A1  - Ljt B. 
Y1  - 1971//
N2  - A study of the effect of prenatal testosterone injections upon the ovarian function of the rat offspring. Two forms of testosterone were used: propionate in oil and hemisuccinate in aqueous solution. The injections were administered by different routes: subcutaneous, intraperitoneal intrauterine extra amniotic, and intra amniotic. The destructive action of testosterone propionate upon gestation was confirmed, since, after repeated subcutaneous injections, surviving litters were obtained in only 25.81 But these injections did not impede the normal function of the ovary in the offspring. In these rats, the decreased percentage of pregnancies was due to an anatomic abnormality of the vagina rather than to ovarian dysfunctions. Intraperitioneal and intrauterine extra amniotic produced similar results. On the other hand, intra amniotic injection produced anovulatory ovaries in almost two thirds of the cases. This effect is due to a specific action of the hormone. Injection of pure oil into the amniotic bag did not disturb the future ovarian function of the offspring. Testosterone hemisuccinate is ineffective in whatever form it is administered. The same negative result is obtained if a single injection of hemisuccinate is given to the newborn rat Only repeated injections and higher dosages produce a sterilizing effect in 502 of the cases. This indicates that the difference between the action of propionate and hemisuccinate is due to the accelerated elimination and/or inactivation of the hormone when administered in aqueous solution. The results of the intra amniotic administration of testosterone propionate prove that the hypophyseal hypothalamic response of the female rat to testosterone is not limited to the first 5 days of extrauterine life but is already present in the prenatal period.
