Y1  - 1971//
N2  - Changes were studied in the acid base balance in the blood of 46 premature infants with respiratory disease and in a group of 50 healthy controls on the 3rd, 7th, 10th and 60th days of life. Some of the children also had the serum electrolytes estimated. Most of the children in both groups up to the 10th day of life showed a mixed acidosis, which proved more pronounced among the ill group (healthy controls: pH 7. 36, pCO, 40. 67, BE -3. 44; diseased: Diseased: pH 129, pCO, 4924, BE -7. 72). Around the 30th day of life the acidosis begins to decline (healthy controls: pH 7. 40, pCO, 3824, BE -1. 33; diseased: pH 7. 36, pCO, 41. 68, BE -127). At 2 mth the acidosis has disappeared (healthy controls: pH 7. 41, pCO, 46. 59, BE +1. 89; diseased: pH 7. 38, pCO, 48. 80, BE +1. 40). In the course of respiratory disease accompanied by acidosis the levels of serum potassium and sodium are elevated and their excretion in the urine is diminished. With the improvement in pulmonary function and increasing age, the electrolyte clearance improves.
