N2  - Vaginal cytograms obtained from patients with gynecologic endocrine disorders were analyzed retrospectively. The phenomenon of a relative increase in cyanophilic superficial cells is recognized commonly in anovulatory cycles due to various causes. However, a predominant increase in cyanophilic superficial cells does not occur in an anovulatory cycle due to hypprestrogenism, or arnenorrhea due to pituitary failure. Tinctorial differentiation of the cytoplasm as well as the recognition of pyknotic nuclei are extremely important in appreciating the relative increase in cyanophilic superficial cells. In the evaluation of vaginal cytograms, it is recommended that the total superficial cell count be divided into two parts, eosinophilic and cyanophilic.
