AN  - 292107022
T1  - Gas to blood PCO2 differences during rebreathing in children and adults
A1  - Godfrey S.
A1  - Katzenelson R.
A1  - Wolf E. 
Y1  - 1971//
N2  - The alveolar to blood PCO2 difference during rebreathing, which abolished CO2 exchange in the lung, has been studied in 3 children aged 9 to 10 years and 3 adults 23 to 24 years. The blood PCO2 was measured from an arterialised ear lobe sample taken after recirculation had begun. The gas PCO2 was measured from the end tidal record at the mid point of blood sampling, with appropriate allowance for the time lag from lung to ear. Alveolar PCO2 was consistently higher than blood PCO 2 by an amount which increased with the work load. The cardiac output calculated by using the uncorrected gas equilibrium PCO2 gave the most reasonable results in all subjects. There were no differences in alveolar to blood gradient or in cardiac output for a given oxygen consumption between children and adults. The reason for the large gas to blood differences using the present technique is discussed and the problem posed by these studies is noted.
