T1  - Hypocapnia induced increases in rectal temperature in man daring heat exposure
A1  - Robinson S.M.
A1  - King A.B. 
Y1  - 1971//
N2  - The possible contribution of hyperventilation and the associated hypocapnia to an elevation of rectal temperature in heat stress was suggested by reports that hyperventilation decreases sweat rate in the heat and reduces skin blood flow at normal ambient temperatures. To study this possibility, seven subjects were exposed to the heat (40.6'C, 104 RH) for two sessions 1 week apart. The subjects hyperventilated for 60 minutes at 34 times their normal ventilation; in one session, base tine levels of end tidal pCO, were maintained by addition of CO, to the inspiratory air line. Determinations were made of rectal temperature, skin temperature, sweat rate, forearm and hand blood flow, ventilation rate, and end tidal pCO, Hypocapnic hyperventilation at 40.6C was accompanied by a significant rise in rectal temperature, a transient decrease in sweat rate, and a reduction in skin blood flow, relative to the isocapnic control values. The data suggest that the accelerated rise in rectal temperature associated with hypocapnia may be explained by a blood flow shift away from the relatively cool skin, possibly augmented by an inadequate sweat rate.
