8834. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 291050100
T1  - Cerebral blood how during and after hyperventilation
A1  - Raichle M.E.
A1  - Posner J.B.
A1  - Plum F. 
Y1  - 1970//
N2  - Hypocapnia was produced by hyperventilation in experimental animals and man to test the hypothesis that brain interstitial pH is a major factor controlling cerebral blood flow (CBP). The rationale was that hyperventilation produces an initial rise in brain interstitial and CSF pH, but the pH gradually falls toward normal over several hours of continued hypocapnia and becomes relatively acid when the control arterial carbon dioxide tension PCO2 is restored. If CSF pH controls the cerebral vascular resistance (CVR), hyperventilation should initially decrease the CBF as CSF pH rises, but CBF should gradually return toward control while hyperventilation continues and overshoot' control when normocapnia is restored. In 11 paralyzed hyperventilated dogs CBF fell about 60% within 30 minutes and declined a further ffi over the next five hours. The CBF after restoration of normocapnia was not significantly different from the control value. Blood pressure and cerebral metabolism did not change significantly. As a control 11 other animals were anesthetized, paralyzed, and ventilated at normocapnic levels for five hours; over five hours the CBF gradually declined 241 If this 24% expected decline in CBF is compared with the response to hypocapnia of the experimental animals, one can infer that CBF did relatively increase during sustained hyperventilation and exceeded predicted values when normocapnia was restored. In four studies on three unanesthetized voluntarily hyperventilating men, the CBF fell almost Wi, after 30 minutes of PCO2 15 to 20 mm Hg. After four hours of hyperventilation, the CBF had gradually risen to 90% of the control value, and it overshot control by a calculated 31% when the original PCO, was restored. The experiments support the concept that brain interstitial pH is a major factor controlling CBF. The findings also suggest that the paralyzed, passively ventilated dog is a poor model for prolonged experiments in CBF since there is a significant decline in flow over five hours. This decline may explain previous results which appeared to show that the PCO, and not the CSF pH regulated the CBF.
