8843. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 291120433
T1  - Cerebral oedema after cardiac arrest treated by hyperventilation and ventricular drainage of the CSF
A1  - Vapalahti M. 
Y1  - 1970//
N2  - In patients with traumatic cerebral oedema prolonged intraventricular pressure over 60 mmHg predicts almost certain death. Because of some promising results in the treatment of brain injured patients with hyperventilation and ventricular drainage this kind of treatment was tried in a case of brain oedema after cardiac arrest. An 11 yr old boy suddenly fell down while running. Previously, he had been well except for probable mitral stenosis. After resuscitation at the local hospital he started to breath spontaneously but did not regain consciousness. On the third day after cardiac arrest he was still unconscious with brain stem rigidity but breathing spontaneously. Intracranial pressure was about 30 mmHg at first. Cortisone had to be stopped because of gastric bleeding and on the 5th day the pressure gradually rose to 65 mmHg. At this time controlled respiration was begun with reduction of arteriaf pCO 22to 21 mmHg and ventricular drainage of the CSF when pressure was over 35 mmHg. Hyperventilation was stopped on the 8th day and pressure recording on the lith day after c.a. Intraventricular pressure was then almost normal but with narrow spikes to 40 mmHg. The boy did not recover, and is still unconscious 2 months later. Cortisone, hyperventilation and ventricular drainage is suggested for children after cardiac arrest with severe brain damage, in order to reduce additional damage to the oedematous brain.
