8844. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 291120238
T1  - Acid base balance in cerebrospinal fluid: Stability of cerebrospinal fluid pH in systemic acid base balance disorders
A1  - Osaka A. 
Y1  - 1970//
N2  - Arterial and jugular venous blood and CSF acid base were measured in 13 control and 31 patients with chronic acid base disorders. Blood and CSF pH, pCO2and pO2were analyzed anaerobically at 37degreeC with the radiometer microgasanalyzer type TFC-1 The mean values of CSF, arterial and jugular venous blood pH were: controls (13 patients) 7.282 7.404 and 7.357, metabolic acidosis (10 patients) 7.326 7.256 and 7.219, respiratory acidosis (9 patients) 7.233 7.330 and 7.288, metabolic alkalosis (3 patients) 7.377 7.537 and 7.469 and respiratory alkalosis (9 patients) 7.336 7.502 and 7.413 In patients with chronic metabolic acidosis, the CSF pH was within normal limits. CSF arterial pCO, differences narrowed and CSF arterial (HCO3~) differences reversed. In patients with chronic metabolic and respiratory alkalosis, the CSF pH was less alkalotic than the blood. CSF arterial pCO 2(metabolic and respiratory alkalosis) and (HCO3~) differences (respiratory alkalosis) were similar to control values. CSF arterial (HCO3~) widened in metabolic alkalosis. In chronic respiratory acidosis, the CSF pH was relatively more acidotic than blood following a widened CSF arterial (HCO3~) difference and narrowed CSF arterial pCO 2 difference. The constancy of CSF pH in acid base disorders suggests that strong homeostatic mechanisms preserve the pH of brain extracellular space. One effective mechanism appears to be changes in ventilation which affect the CSF pH more than the blood pH. The activity of the medullary (H+) chemoreceptor tends to restore CSF pH towards normal in response to changes in CSF pH by adjusting the level of ventilation and the CSF pCO2. A second mechanism is chemical regulation of CBF in response to changes in arterial pCO2 and pH. The third mechanism controls the CSF (HCO 3~), presumably by active transport of (H+) or (HCO3~). The CSF (H+) is regulated by an active transport process across the blood CSF barrier which adjusts CSF (HCO3~) responding to changes in CSF pCO2. It is possible that there are other, as yet undiscovered regulatory systems.
