8845. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 292067090
T1  - Fetal acid base homeostasis
A1  - Blechner T.N. 
Y1  - 1970//
N2  - Fetal acid base homeostasis is regulated to a considerable degree by the selective treatment of carbon dioxide and bicarbonate ion by the placenta. Animal studies demonstrate this principle, and human observations confirm its validity in human pregnancy. The placental transfer of carbon dioxide from fetus to mother is adequate to handle the metabolic production of CO, by the fetus and to maintain fetal homeostasis. In situations in which the maternal carbon dioxide tension changes, whether during postoperative recovery or during infusion of ammonium chloride, the pCO2 of the fetal blood is distinctly dependent upon the maternal. Moreover, acute respiratory acidosis in the mother is followed by immediate respiratory acidosis in the fetus indicating that the placental barrier is very permeable to carbon dioxide. Maternal respiratory acidosis or alkalosis causes simultaneous changes in the fetus because uncharged CO2 molecules traverse the placenta freely. Metabolic alterations dependent upon bicarbonate ions, however, do not necessarily induce similar acid base changes in the fetus. Under several conditions studied, the bicarbonate ion concentration in fetal plasma is virtually independent of the maternal indicating that the placental barrier is poorly permeable to bicarbonate. This limitation may be associated with the electrical charge of the bicarbonate ion. The acids produced in diabetes meUitus have not been studied, however, and the results cited here cannot be used to predict the effects of diabetic acidosis on fetal acid base balance. Observations in human pregnancy demonstrate that fetal or neonatal acidosis does not necessarily accompany maternal metabolic acidosis. Fetal plasma bicarbonate and pH remain relatively unchanged despite significant reductions in the mothers levels. There appears to be a limitation in placenta! permeability to hydrogen and bicarbonate ions that exerts a profound regulatory effect on the acid base balance of the human fetus. On one hand, the fetus is capable of using his placenta to protect his internal milieu from the effects of certain types of maternal metabolic acidosis. On the other hand, his carbon dioxide tension is determined by the level in the maternal blood perfusing the placenta, and there is no tendency for the pCO, of the fetal blood to be regulated as such. Since pH depends on the ratio of bicarbonate to CO., the independence of fetal bicarbonate confers upon the fetus a similar independence of pH and permits the fetus to be acidotic or alkalotic with respect to the mother. Finally, the difference in the degree of dependence of the fetal pCO, and bicarbonate concentration upon the maternal can result in paradoxical pH changes with a maternal metabolic acidosis causing a fetal respiratory alkalosis.
