8847. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 290073988
T1  - Investigations on the antibody formation in women treated with FSH active sheep pituitary gonadotrophin
A1  - Daume E.
A1  - Muller H.L.
A1  - Villinger W. 
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Nine women suffering from anovulatory ovarian insufficiency received FSH active material of sheep pituitary origin (SH 820, Schering AG, Berlin) to induce ovulations. The doses administered varied between 10 and 22.5 mg of the substance per day for 10 days on the average. A total of 14 courses of such treatments was performed, 4 women had 1 series, 4 women 2 series and one woman 4 series of injections. Serum was obtained prior to and at various times up to 10 mth following such therapy. To demonstrate possible antibody formation, the technique of Middlebrook et al. (1948) and Boyden (1950) was employed. This technique was first tested as a model. Rabbits were sensitized by injections of sheep pituitary extract With the hemagglutination reaction using human group O erythrocytes, which were coated with antigen, antibodies in rabbit serum could be demonstrated. In human serum obtained either before or at various times following treatment with sheep pituitary FSH active gonadotrophin antibodies were not found using this same technique. Using unaensitized sheep erythrocytes instead of coated human group O erythrocytes in the hemagglutination reaction 3 out of the apatients were found to have titers already prior to the treatment. Following therapy occurrence of titers and titer increases were relatively small in 6 patients and absent in 2. In 1 case titers rose to 1:320 in the 3rd month after therapy. From these preliminary data it is suggested that therapy with sheep pituitary FSH active gonadotrophin in an effective dose to stimulate ovarian function even if repeated 3 times, is not capable of inducing the formation of specific antibodies against the substance used. Non specific antibodies were observed even in untreated patients, occurrence and titer increases following treatment were small. Further investigations in 20 untreated women showed that these non specific antibodies were present in the serum of 17 patients.
