8851. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 290097468
T1  - Measurement of pulmonary diffusing capacity during blood to gas exchange in humans
A1  - Power G.G.
A1  - Bradford W.C. 
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - The pulmonary diffusing capacity for CO (DL) was studied in six human subjects during blood to gas transfer and compared with conventional, single breath DL in the same subjects. From 69 to 183 ml CO was administered and 40 min later the first of eight determinations was performed. After brief hyperventilation with CO free gas, the rate of increase in alveolar CO was measured during breath holding. Using the subjects' measured alveolar volume and assuming the affinity of Hb for CO relative to O2 was 250, DL' was calculated. At mean capillary PO2 values of 191 and 591 mm Hg DL and DL' were statistically indistinguishable. The findings suggest that the diffusing capacity of the pulmonary membrane and of pulmonary capillary blood does not vary with the direction of gas transfer. Conventional DL did not change measurably when the PCO of the test gas was decreased to 1/15 of control levels. The conclusions are the pulmonary and red cell membranes are isotropic for CO, evidence is not discovered for facilitated or active transfer of CO, and the diffusing capacity of CO in whole blood is the same for gas transfer from the plasma to the red cell interior and in the reverse direction.
