8857. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 289035592
T1  - Vaginal cytology in childhood and puberty. II. Puberty
A1  - Sonek M. 
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - The aim of this paper was to discuss the cytologic patterns found in childhood and puberty, based on the results of cytologic examinations of 881 female children and young girls. The results of cytologic serial examinations of 250 newborns are in accordance with the results reported by other authors. The division in specific time periods, as given by Pundel, vary slightly, especially regarding the length of time of the transition period into the atrophic period. According to the results, this period is longer than reported by Pundel and more variable. It was also found that newborns with a heavy icterus neonatorum showed less proliferation in the cytologic specimen than those infants with a heavy jaundice. During the atrophic stage of childhood the appearance of autolyzed parabasal cells predominated in the cytologic pattern. This pattern changes at the end of the atrophic period into a pattern with well preserved parabasal cells. Mixed patterns are characteristic for the prepubertal period. Cytologic features which can be used in the differential diagnosis of precocious puberty are briefly reported. Isosexual precocious puberty manifests itself by proliferation of the superficial layer only. Heterosexual precocious puberty is characterized by proliferation even to the intermediate layer. In girls aged 12 to 15 yr anovulatory cycles were found in 90.6%. The anovulatory cycles were divided according to proliferation levels into the phase of increase, the peak, and the phase of decrease as follows: normoestrogenic cycles, 44.8%; hypoestrogenic cycles, 20.7%; hyperestrogenic cycles, 30.3%. The practical application of vaginal cytology in childhood and puberty is briefly summarized.
