8858. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 289091573
T1  - Hypercapnia in pulmonary disease
A1  - Howell J.B.L.
A1  - Lane D.L. 
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - Hypercapnia occurs in pulmonary disease usually in association with increased resistance to airflow through the bronchial tree. Two different types of association may be recognized. In one the patient tries to breathe more but cannot because the resistances to ventilation are too great; in the other, the patient is able to breathe more but does not try. If one follows the clinical course of a patient of the first type, one may observe a progressive reduction in the maximum ventilatory capacity without any detectable alveolar hypoventilation until a lower limit is reached below which a rapid reduction in alveolar ventilation occurs as shown by an increased Pcos. These patients are extremely dyspnoeic, are not hypoxic and have normal or near normal CO 2 sensitivity as estimated by the increase in inspiratory muscle power recruited by an increment in PcO2. It appears that, despite such compensatory factors as increased lung volume and increased respiratory frequency, maximum expiratory airflow is so reduced by flow limiting mechanisms thai adequate ventilation is mechanically impossible. In the second type, the failure to maintain normal alveolar ventilation is associated with a reduction in the sensitivity of the respiratory center to CO,. The patient characteristically has a long history of purulent bronchitis and presents with cyanosis, polycythernia, pulmonary hypertension und edema. Although airway obstruction may sometimes be severe, it is often only moderate und it can then be shown that mechanical factors do not influence the level of ventilation except at high rates of airflow. The reasons for the impaired responsiveness to CO2 are not known. Sonic possibilities were considered.
