8859. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 290035970
T1  - A new theory for the regulation of the extracellular ph in the brain -
A1  - Siesjo B.K.
A1  - Kjallquist A.- 
Y1  - 1969//
N2  - The present theory assumes that the main regulatory mechanism for the CSF pH is the variation of the CSF/plasma potential with the plasma pH. However, since the blood CSF barriei does not act as a perfect hydrogen ion electrode, it is thought that factors which regulate plasma pH (regulation of plasma pCO 2 by lung ventilation, regulation of the plasma bicarbonate by the kidneys) play an important role in keeping the CSF pH close to the normal value. In hyperventilation, the outflux of lactic acid from the tissue cells becomes of importance in the CSF pH regulation. It is further assumed that the electrochemical H+ disequilibrium, i.e. ilif nri p.mJ. between CSF and plasma, is caused by a secretion of hydrogen ions by a kidney type mechanism which is dependent on the CO2 tension, and on the presence of carbonic anhydrase. However, since this secretion of H+ is triggered by the CO2 tension, and not by the CSF or the plasma pH, it will not contribute significantly to the CSF pH control in nonrespiratory acid base conditions, and it will tend to counteract CSF pH stability in hypercapnia and hypocapnia. Presumably, it is involved in the control of pH in the intracellular spaces. This theory appears to explain many of the unexplained features of the CSF pH regulation. The pH stability in non-respiratory acidosis and alkalosis is explained by the large changes in the electrical potential and possibly also the slight tendency of the H+ secretion to change in a direction favouring pH stability (effect of CO2 tension). It may be assumed that the marked changes of the potential in the alkaline direction explains why the CSF pH appears more stable in alkalosis than in acidosis. In respiratory alkalosis one may expect pH stability due to the marked changes in the electrical potential and to the progressive increase in the outflux of lactic acid. The failure of the CSF pH to remain normal in respiratory acidosis is explained by the relatively smaller potential change, by the inefficiency of the lactic acid regulation in acidosis, and by the increased secretion of hydrogen ions into the CSF. One can explain the high in vivo CO2 buffer capacity of the CSF. Thus, in subacute respiratory acidosis the plasma acidosis will be limited only by the moderate increase in the bicarbonate concentration, while the CSF bicarbonate will increase considerably more, owing to the combined effect of the increased plasma bicarbonate, and the increased (positive) potential. In the chronic state, the buffering of the plasma will increase, owing to renal retention of bicarbonate, but the buffering of the CSP will stay more constant, since the effect of the increased plasma bicarbonate will be counteracted by the decrease in the CSF/plasma potential, which occurs concomitantly to the normalization of the plasma pH.
