8861. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 290053925
T1  - Cellular membranes: the isolation and characterisation of the plasma and smooth membranes of hela cells
A1  - Bosmann H.B.
A1  - Hagopian A.
A1  - Eylar E.H. 
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A method is described for preparation of membrane fractions from the 4000g supernatant fluid, obtained from a Bounce homogenate of HeLa cells, using a discontinuous sucrose gradient (20-452 sucrose). Two fractions were obtained, the plasma membranes and the smooth internal membranes that appeared by electron microscopy to be free of nuclei, mitochondria, lysosomes, microsomes, fibrosomes, dense bodies, or other recognizable cellular elements. The integrity of the plasma membranes were preserved as shown by electron microscopic examination: ruptured cellular envelopes were seen by phase microscopy. The degree of purity of the plasma membranes was shown by high increase in specific activity of the 5' nucleotidase over the cellular homogenate of 120 fold. In contrast to the plasma membranes, found as a pellet below the 452 sucrose, the smooth internal membranes were found above the 252 sucrose level. The two membrane preparations revealed marked differences. The plasma membranes were purified approximately 120 fold based on the increase in specific activity of the 5degree nucleotidase. an enzyme found exclusively in these membranes, but not detected in the smooth membranes. The latter membranes also lacked ATPase, which was purified 30 fold during the course of preparation of the plasma membranes, but had a relatively high UDPase activity, an enzyme absent from plasma membranes. The plasma membranes had a high molar ratio of cholesterol to phospholipid of 1.05; in the smooth membranes this ratio was 0.06. These results clearly differentiate structural and biological properties of these membranes.
