A1  - Morris R. 
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - Two factorial experiments are described in each of which 4 women were treated with human gonadotrophins for failure of ovulation. Pituitary follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) was used in one, and a commercial preparation of human menopausal gonadotrophins (HMG) from urine (Pergonal) in the other. Treatment varied from giving the whole dose in a single injection to equally divided doses for up to 4 days in succession. Human chorionic gonadotrophin (HCG) was invariably given afterwards, either on the 7th or on the 10th day after starting each course of treatment. The excretion of oestriol reached a peak on days 7 and 8 when HCG was given on day 10, and on days 9 and 10 when it was given on day 7. HCG on day 7 also caused a delay in the subsequent fall in excretion on days 11 and 12 A similar effect was caused by giving FSH or HMG in divided doses over 4 days compared with giving the whole dose on day 1. These differences were significant in the second experiment but not in the first, in which the experimental error was much greater. An analysis of 281 mth of treatment showed: (1) when FSH was mixed with HRG and given as a single injection on day 1 the average peak in excretion of oestriol occurred a day later than when FSH was given alone; (2) when FSH was spread over 8 days the average peak occurred on day 11. Both these differences were highly significant. Pregnancy occurred in only 13% of the months in which ovulation was deemed to have occurred when patients were given FSH alone as a single injection on day 1 followed by HCG on day 10; it occurred in 27% of these occasions when the FSH was mixed with HCG. This difference was significant at the 10% level. This treatment, however, was associated with a relatively high incidence of follicular development with ovulation, and it is concluded that the best method of treatment is with 3 injections of FSH on days 1, 4, and 8, followed by HCG on day 10. The analyses revealed a previously unrecorded joint action of FSH and HCG.
