8871. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 289033865
T1  - Psychologic correlates of the polycystic ovary syndrome and organic infertility
A1  - Nesbitt Jr. R.E.L.
A1  - Hollender M.
A1  - Fisher S.
A1  - Osofsky H.J. 
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - A total of 36 adult females ranging in age from 20 to 39, who had been characterized as either infertile or normal, were subjected to intensive psychiatric and psychologic investigation. The women were subdivided into 3 groups: those with polycystic ovary syndrome (10 patients), those with infertility secondary to organic pelvic pathology (8 patients), and normal fertile subjects selected as controls (18 patients). The psychiatric depth interviews revealed few, if any, real differences between the polycystic ovary group and the organic infertile group, although there was a trend for the patients with the polycystic ovary syndrome to be less interested in the kinds of play which one associates with an attempt to identify with the mother and the mothering role. There were some interesting reactions among the infertile women to the state of childlessness itself, which not only interfered with sexual gratification but also placed a strain on the total marital relationship. The polycystic ovary and the organic infertile groups could not be distinguished on the basis of psychologic tests and no dependable correlates of the polycystic ovary syndrome were discernible. However, in contrast with normal controls, there was a definite tendency for the infertile women, considered as a group, to manifest particular problems linked to their need to maintain a high level of narcissistic gratification and to avoid having to contribute energy to others (nurturance). These responses to objective tests were congruent with the clinically observed evidences of ambivalence toward motherhood displayed by many of these women. Doubts about their own femininity and adequacy were intensified by their infrequent menses and their childlessness. Since motherhood itself can serve as a growth experience for women, the particular anxiety and reactions evidenced by the infertile group may represent not a longterm, basic problem, but may rather be a result of longstanding infertility. These emotional factors, whether primary or secondary, must be given attention in treating infertile patients, since these women have considerable adjustments to make in their concepts of femininity in general, and in their marriage and sexual activities in particular.
