8872. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 289070399
T1  - Regional pulmonary blood flow and gas exchange in hemorrhagic shock
A1  - Naimark A.
A1  - Dugard A.
A1  - Rangno R.E. 
Y1  - 1968//
N2  - The effects of hemorrhage on relative regional pulmonary blood flow (RPBF Xe122 technique) and gas exchange were studied in anesthetized mongrel dogs. In the early stages of hypotension there was a decrease in RPBF of upper lung zones which coincided with a decrease in pulmonary artery pressure and cardiac output and an increased arterial-end-tidal PCO, difference. Later, during shock (uptake of shed blood, severe acidemia), RFBF became uniform again but the increased arterial-end-tidal PCO, difference persisted and an increased alveolar.arterial PO2 difference was noted. After infusion of the remaining shed blood, pulmonary artery pressure returned to control levels or higher but the cardiac output remained low and the gas tension differences were still elevated. Postmortem examination revealed variable decrees of focal atelectasis and edema in dependent lung zones. It is postulated that in simple hemorrhage hypotension the increased alveolar dead space is mainly the result of gravity-dependent hypoperfusion of upper lung zones; whereas when shock supervenes, severe acidemia und structural derangements contribute to the hypoperfusion and increased alveolar dead space.
