8879. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 288088608
T1  - Contractility of the nonpregnant human uterus
A1  - Anonymous.
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - The problem of the spontaneous contractility of the nonpregnant human uterus has been reassessed using the open-end intrauterine-catheter method in 20 patients. Endometrial biopsies and/or BBT were obtained as an adjunct to correlate the recordings with hormonal changes of the ovarian cycle. In the proliferative phase of the normal cycle, the basic pattern is constituted by frequent. moderate contractions which show cyclic variation. Immediately preceding and following ovulation, the intensity of contractions is markedly diminished. Under the influence of the corpus luteum some large, slow, infrequent complexes appear, be coming later the predominant pattern; superimposed upon these there are still present some small and frequent contractions. During early menstruation the contractions are very strong, regular, 'labor-like', evolving towards uncoordinated, weaker contractions as the days pass. Finally, the evolution ends in the moderate, frequent proliferative pattern. The relatively quiescent period of midcycle has been recorded in a case around the period of implantation of a pregnancy which terminated successfully. In the anovulatory cycle only a proliferative type pattern was recorded throughout the contractions of menstruation being similar to those obtained in biphasic cycles. Under treatment with norethynodrel-mestranol it was possible to reproduce the contractility pattern of the secretory phase. Under this condition, as in spontaneous secretory phase, a characteristic uterine response to awakening was recorded: a quick, strong contraction, absent in the proliferative phase, anovulatory cycle, and menstruation. Several years after menopause the contractions are weak and irregular; in a case of granulosa-cell tumor of the ovary the uterine activity was very high, with a proliferative phase pattern. The pertinent literature has been reviewed and discussed, with emphasis on factors controlling the uterine contractility. A tentative explanation for the mechanism of action of estrogen-progesterone has been postulated.
