N2  - McArdle found that l min exercise performed during 3 min ischemia was followed by increase in forearm blood flow and decrease in venous blood lactate in a subject with abnormal muscle carbohydrate metabolism which was later shown to be due to deficiency in phosphorylase. T ob in and Coleman found that the same ischemie exercise on venous blood pH and lactate in 3 siblings with phosphorylase deficiency was accompanied by little change in venous blood pH or lactate in the siblings, whereas in a normal subject pH decreased and lactate increased. In an experiment on McArdle's patient opening and closing of his palm once every 2 sec for 3 min did not alter deep venous blood pH or PCOZ (Severinghaus electrode); lactate decreased about 2 mg/100 g. Postexercise forearm blood flow increased from 3 to 35 ml/ 100 ml forearm/min. The results confirm those of previous authors. They show that the hyperemia of exercise took place although there was no decrease in pH, increase in PCO<< or increase in blood lactate. (H, 8A).
