8889. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 289108979
T1  - Principles and a recommendation for fluid therapy in pediatric surgery particularlyin open-heart surgery under cardio-pulmonary bypass
A1  - Maruno
A1  - Fukui A.
A1  - Takayama N. 
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - External and/or internal balances during preoperative (3 cases), operative (8 cases) and postoperative (9 cases) parenteral fluid therapy confirmed that the principle of fluid therapy in surgical conditions in the pediatric field is preoperatively to repair the previous deficits of water and electrolytes and to provide during operative or postoperative periods with maintenance requirements for continuing abnormal losses. Intravenous drip of 5% glucose alone or with whole blood during operation is not recommendable, although common practice, since such operative fluid therapy evokes a deficit of electrolytes toward the end of the operative procedure, especially with the abnormal losses of body fluid through suction, drainage or intubation. In the same way, the fluid to be administered postoperatively should not only contain glucose but also electrolytes to meet daily maintenance requirments. Although no trend or antidiuresis or oliguria has been observed postoperatively in the present case, the possible mechanism for postoperative retention of sodium and water was discussed in association with the same phenomena commonly observed after severe burns. While these principles are subject to open heart surgery as well, the acid-base management is another key point for its successful outcome. Metabolic acidosis, which results from poor perfusion of peripheral tissue and is assumed to lower the cardiac output, is the most frequent occurrence during bypass. Toward the end of bypass procedures, sodium bicarbonate should be added to the maintenance need for electrolytes to repair buffer base deficits. Another acid-base derangement commonly encountered in open heart surgery is respiratory acidosis resulting from inadequate ventilation and its adverse situation of respiratory alkalosis caused by hyperventilation incident to the over use of mechanical ventilator. The latter is more hazardous since decrement of pCO 2 induces shift of the hemoglobin/oxygen dissociation curve to the left and evokes a state of hypoxia in the tissue. When hypothermia is employed, the optimal pH is not 7.4 but should be reduced from it by 0.0147 of a pH unit for each degree celsius below 37, and this is conveniently achieved by mixing carbon dioxide in the pump oxygenator. A recommendation has been made for simplifying the scheme of parenteral fluid therapy for pediatric surgery in relation to newly developed multielectrolyte solutions.
