8890. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 288032824
T1  - A review of 307 cases of infertility -
A1  - Baeyertz J.D. 
Y1  - 1967//
N2  - A detailed analysis is presented of a 91% followup of 307 primary and secondary infertility patients seen in private consultant practice over a period of 8 yr. and reference is made to the work of other authors in this field. 162 patients conceived. There were 146 (90%) livebirths. 252 patients had tests of tubal patency and in 32 of these (12.5%) the tubes were considered to be blocked, yet 4 conceived. The overall conception rate in the remaining 220 women with patent tubes was 55% and 73% of these conceptions occurred within 6 mth. The question of the prognostic and therapeutic value of the various procedures employed in the diagnosis, establishment, and maintenance of tubal patency is fully discussed. Full sperm counts were undertaken in 158 patients. Ten (6.3%) had azoospermia and none of these conceived. A further 16 (10%) had counts below 10 million/ml and only 6 conceived (37%), but the pregnancy rate in the primary infertility group with these subnormal counts was lower (27%) than that in the secondary infertility group (60%). The conception rate for those with counts between 10 and 60 million/ml was 62%. Hormonal factors were significant in 34 patients (11%) and 74% conceived. The use of hormones in infertility is discussed. Of 165 women investigated by curettage, only 4 (2.5%) showed apparently genuine anovulation and 3 of these conceived subsequently without treatment. Two patients were found to have tuberculosis of the endometrium neither conceived. Endometriosis was considered to be present in 20 women (6.5%) and, despite all therapy, only 3 (15%) conceived. Pregnancy rates in the general population and in untreated infertile patients are discussed. Of the 307 infertile patients seen, 48 decided to adopt (15.7%). Eleven of these subsequently conceived, but since 8 of the group were sterile, the corrected conception rate in adopting parents was 27.5%. The latter patients belonged to a group who were likely to conceive sooner or later and there was little evidence to suggest that the act of adoption facilitated conception. Final conclusions on the whole subject of infertility are presented. (10, 17).
