T1  - Neonatal thyhoidology: correlations of pbi. tbg, bone age and growth
A1  - Lindegren L.
A1  - Starr P. 
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - Umbilical cord and serial venous PBI, cholesterol, TBG, and TBPA measurements were made on 300 human infants; X-ray for bone age, height age and weight age, clinical and neurologic evaluations were done at birth; at 3 mth. 128 mothers and babies returned for these tests; and at 6 mth. only 52 returned. The results show an extreme range of PBI values in both mothers and babies; no correlation between the PBI of the baby and the mothers; no correlation between the umbilical cord PBI and TBG or TBPA, or the sum of these. At 3 mth. the babies' mean PBI and range of PBI was of the same magnitude at>> in the cord blood but there was no correlation between the individual values at birth and 3 mth, The mean serum cholesterol in the cord blood was 90.5 mg/100 ml and 181.0 mg/100 ml at 3 mth. In two thirds of the 49 infante in whom PBI values were recorded at birth and at 3 and 6 mth., the variation between the lowest and highest value was frequently 2- or 3-fold. The distal femoral epiphyses were smaller in infants whose umbilical vein serum PBI concentration was less than 5/100 ml as compared to those with higher PBIs. But, at 3 mth. of age. the serum PBI relationships were frequently reversed and the bone age appeared normal. Finally, at 6 mth. of age there was no consistent quantitative relationship between the serum PBI value, height age, and bone age. Fourteen children were suspected of hypothyroidism; 2 of 52 at 6 mth. of age were finally put on maintenance treatment with thyroxine.
