8897. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 287049661
T1  - The luxury-perfusion syndrome and its possible relation to acute metabolic acidosis localised within the brain
A1  - Lassen N.A. 
Y1  - 1966//
N2  - An acute derangement of the cerebral circulation associated with severe brain damage is described. It is characterized by an over-abundant cerebral blood-flow relative to the metabolic needs of the brain tissue, and it is therefore called the luxury-perfusion syndrome. The existence or relative cereorai hyperemia implies that the cerebral arteriovenous difference of oxygen is abnormally small. In other words when the pulmonary circulation is normal the condition is revealed by an unusually high saturation of the cerebral venous blood: this bright-red venous blood is a cardinal feature of the syndrome. The luxury-perfusion syndrome is thought to be of considerable importance in relation to the pathophysiology of many acute brain diseases, notably apoplexy and acute neurosurgical conditions. There is a striking similarity between the concepts of the regulation of the cerebral circulation described here and current theories of the regulation of the respiration by a carbon-dioxide-sensitive chemoreceptor zone in the medulla oblongata. In both, the system seems to react much as a Severinghaus PCO? electrode. This instrument measures PcO2 through the changes of pH in a dilute solution of bicarbonate behind a semipermcable 'Teflon* membrane. This is also the model of the regulation of the tone of the cerebral arterioles and of the medullary respiratory center. In both cases the basic stimulus is a tissue pH determined by the PCOZ of that tissue (the blood itself in the case of the arterioles) and by the bicarbonate content of the surrounding cerebrospinal fluid. If the bicarbonate concentration is lowered for some reason, then both systems (as in the Fo2 electrode) must interpret a normal N(>2 a s if it was increased and counter-regulatory mechanisms (hyperfusion and hyperpnoea) will set in. The similarity may be considered as not only apparent: the respiration and the cerebral circulation would seem together to form a single homostatic system subserving the gas exchange of the brain.
