8904. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 286043794
T1  - COAGULATION and FIBRINOLYTIC STUDIES in WOMEN RECEIVING AN ANOVULATORY DRUG (MEDROXY-PROGESTERONE ACETATE with ESTRADIOL)
A1  - Powell L.C.
A1  - Guest M.M.
A1  - Bond T.P. 
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Since the introduction of contraceptive agents containing progestins, a number of minor side effects have been noted, but the serious implication that these drugs cause hypercoagulability, thrombosis and thromboemholism has also been raised. Sixteen subjects were investigated in the present study: all but 2 received Provest, and 2 volunteers not treated with these agents were studied as controls. There were 142 treatment cycles observed: the incidence of break-through bleeding, nausea, fluid retention, nervousness and effect on libido is reported in detail and no thrombotic phenomena of masculinization was seen. Blood samples were drawn under standard conditions for determination of partial thromboplastin time, serum prothrombin, antifibrinolysis, fibrinogen and fibrinolytic potential. In 8 of the treated subjects these studies were sufficiently complete to justify their statistical evaluation. No significant variations in coagulation or fibrinolytic components were found when comparing the treated subjects with controls. This study gives no indication of a hypercoagulable state due to Prevest. Reports from other laboratories have been conflicting. Even if a change in activity in 1 coagulation factor due to a progestin can be demonstrated, it does not necessarily predispose to thrombosis, since compensatory mechanisms may more than compensate. Sturgis - Boston, Mass. (X, 3. 5, 6).
