8909. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 286078458
T1  - Diffusion of carbon dioxide out of the distal nephron in man during antidiuresis -
A1  - Reid E.L.
A1  - Hills A.G. 
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - The effects of water diuresis on the composition of urine were studied in healthy men. Whenever urine pH is 6.66 or above at maximum flow both pH and PCO, of urine vary inversely with flow rate. Whenever urine pH at maximal flow is below 6.43, pH varies directly with urine flow, as does PCO, whenever the urine pH is below 6.2. The rate of excretion of HCO3 always decreases markedly as flow declines, although its concentration rises. It is inferred that CO2 is increasingly reabsorbed from the distal nephron as a direct consequence of water reabsorption down the concentration gradient so produced, while HCO3- is restrained within the lumen as urine flow declines. This process results in a rise of pH in bicarbonaterich urine, since H+ is consumed in the conversion of HCO3- to H2CO3- The elevation of urinar Pro. of voided urine above tissue PCO. appears to result from continued dehyds ition. beyond the papilla, of urinary H2CO3 which is present there at a concentration greater than the equilibrium value for the bicarbonate buffer system. This elevation of [H2CO3] is ascribed to generation of H2CO3 at a more rapid rate than it can be nonenzymatically dehydrated in the distal nephron; the generation of H2CO3 results from reaction of HCO3- with H+; either (a) (during diuresis) that secretes into the lumen or (b) (during low flow) that yielded by urinary buffers in consequence of the reabsorption of CO2 down the gradient produced by water reabsorption. When the urine is bicarbonate-rich the latter process produces much greater elevation of PCO than does the former.
