8912. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 286074785
T1  - The 'early-androgen' syndrome; effects of pre-natal testosterone propionate -
A1  - Swanson H.E. 
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Doses of 10 and 25 mg testosterone propionate (TP) given to pregnant rats could induce the eariy-androgen syndrome. These doses caused delayed parturition with intrauterine death and inhibition of lactation with early postnatal death of the young; these events could be avoided by cesarean section and nursing on foster mothers. In other experiments TP was injected directly into the fetuses or their amniotic sacs. A dose of 20 /ug into the amniotic sac was without effect on subsequent ovarian activity and, with 1 exception, on the external genitalia of the young. Injection of 20 or 100 Mg into the fetus caused both external masculinization and anovulatory ovaries. The apparent low sensitivity of the fetus to TP injected into the pregnant doe seems to be due to poor transmission of the steroid from the maternal into the fetal body. The fetal external genitalia appear to be more sensitive to TP than the mechanism which sets the future gonadotropic pattern of the brain-pituitary complex.
