8918. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 287124633
T1  - Disturbed fertility arising from adrfno-genital disorders. the part played by roentgenological examination
A1  - Silin-kova Malkova E. 
Y1  - 1965//
N2  - Disturbances of fertility arising from adrenal or genital disorders are very often caused by morphologic changes which may be disclosed by roentgenologic methods. Most important results are obtained by pneumoretroperitoneum, pneumopelvigraphy. with additional tomography and vagino-, cysto- and/or angiography. In inherited lesions fertility is mostly impossible, malformations of external genitals and changes of the somatic appearance occur frequently. Roentgenologic examination shows enlarged hyperplastic adrenals in the mopelvigraphy, demonstrating the female pelvic structures, is very helpful for the determination of the true sex in virilized female children and for the distinction between the congenital adrenogenital syndrome and intersex, due to chromosomal aberrations (6 cases). The clear and reliable pneu mope Iv igraphic results in gonadal dysgenesis (32 cases) and absence of the uterus {4 cases) help to save useless therapeutic attempts, with regard to fertility. In acquired lesions the change of restoring fertility is better. In virilizing syndromes the underlying cause may be evidenced by pneumoretroperitoneum, if arising from hyperplasia or a tumor of the adrenals (30 observations), or by pneumopelvigraphy if due to an arrhenoblastoma (1 case). Underdeveloped ovaries and uterus are found in ovarian hypofunction of central or local origin. In cases with Stein-Leventhal' s syndrome (123 observations) the clinical suspicion is strongly supported by the pneumopelvigraphic finding of smooth, enlarged ovaries and a small uterus.
