8919. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281586729
T1  - Nentrophil appendages as indicators of sex chromosome aberrations
A1  - Bamford S.B.
A1  - Cassin C.M.
A1  - Dilba D.L.
A1  - Mitchell G.W. 
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - Out of twenty-eight cases presenting with primary or secondary amenorrhea including Stein-Leventhal syndrome, ten with Klinefelter's syndrome, ten with Down's syndrome and infants with multiple congenital anomalies, twelve members of one family with congenital ectodermal dysplasia and twelve normal controls, fourteen cases, all mosaics, were selected as representative of the groups studied. The results of this study are regarded to substantiate the positive role of the neutrophil appendages in the preliminary diagnosis of sex chromosome abnormalities in that: 1. a low incidence of normal drumstick appendages suggests mosaicism with a dominant xo line, while two or more drumstick appendages per cell reflect an increase in the number of x chromosomes per cell; 2. large round drumstick appendages indicate larger metacentric X chromosomes (isochromosomes). 3. small drumsticks appendages, preferable measuring 1.2 micra in diameter, indicate partial deletion of an x chromosome; 4. pure autosomal aberrations do not cause any disturbance in drumstick pattern, as opposed to the combined autosomal and sex chromosomal abnormalities in infants with multiple congenital anomalies. 5. In the case of congenital ectodermal dysplasia, thought to be an autosomal dominant trail, drumstick analysis has led to the prediction of an x chromosome with partial deletion of the upper arms. All karyotypes completed to date have shown partial deletion of one x chromosome. Complete results on a genetic study of the present material will be submitted for publication in the near future.
