8923. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281125967
T1  - Clomiphene citrate: its uses and observations on its probable action
A1  - Whitelaw M.J.
A1  - Grams L.R.
A1  - Stamm W.J. 
Y1  - 1964//
N2  - This report concerns the use of ciomiphene citrate in 70 patients, 55 of whom were married and were seen primarily for infertility. The dosage of the drug varied from 75 to 450 mg., given over a 2 to 5 day period. The best minimum dosage schedule appeared to have been 150 mg. for 2 days and 100 mg. for 2 days. Eighteen were the so-called 'normal' infertility patients who ovulated regularly. Three conceived within the first month and none in the following 5 mth. Ten patients had endometrial hyperplasia, and all responded to treatment by ovulating. Two of the 4 married patients with endometrial hyperplasia conceived within 2 mth. after therapy was started. Sixteen patients with irregular menses varying from 28- to 180-day intervals were treated. Nine of these patients were married, and 5 became pregnant after 1 to 10 mth. of therapy. Twenty-five patients had secondary amenorrhea of over 6 months' duration. Twenty-three of these patients were married and of this number, 16 responded to therapy. Ten of the 16 became pregnant within 6 mth. of onset of therapy. One of the pregnancies resulted in binovular twins. The two single patients in this group responded to therapy. One patient with primary amenorrhea did not respond to therapy. The authors believe, as do Smith, Kistner and Charles that the primary effect of clomiphene citrate is on the ovary, presumably through some enzymatic action. Seven reasons are given to substantiate this hypothesis. The results of clomiphene therapy in cases of so-called Stein-Leventhal syndrome unresponsive to wedge resection have been exceedingly high. All of these patients in the group with irregular menses responded to therapy. The ovulation rate following wedge resection is far less, with some series being as low as 9%.
