N2  - Acid-base determinations were made at catheterization on 4 children with congenital heart disease, who were subsequently cyanosed. It was found that the most constant and normal figure obtained was a systemic arterial pCO 2, which might be a controlling factor in a high respiratory rate ranging from 60 to 78 per min. in these cases. The pulmonary venous pCO 2 was reduced below normal by this respiratory rate, and pO 2 remained normal. The systemic, arterial and pulmonary venous H 2CO3 were both reduced.
