N2  - In a lvcture the autlioi' gives an exposition of the historical past of adenomyosis of the utt.rus, stipulating that in his opinion adenomyosis is invasive endometrial hyperpiasia. The cause of this hyperplasia is not clear. In the author's opinion heredit r.' infIicnr's deserve investigation in connection with his experience concerning the occurrence of adenomyosis in mothers and daughters. Hyperoestrinism is of special importance. According to the author's extensive experience - reproduced in several tables - the rnorphogenesis can be recognized by repeated gynaecological examination, evaluating the muscular hype rtrophy caused b. eudoiretrial invas on, resulting in a rigid, enlarged erect corpus uteri demonstrating fluctuation iii consistency and shape. The functional symptomatology is described. Clinical symptoms and careful naecological examination do not result in a definitely established diagnosis. Office endom etrial biopsy, demotrating anovulatory hyperplasia is of some help. However adc'nomy'sis remains unrecognized in a high percentage of cases. The reverse - a false positive diagnosis - isoffrcquentoccurrence. The lecture is a pica for intensified interest especially in the morphogenesis which clearly resu[ts in a more frequent confirmation by the pathologist of the clinical diagnosis. Daamen - Rotterdarn.
