8938. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281486955
T1  - Induction of ovulation
A1  - Greenblatt R.B.
A1  - Roy S.
A1  - Mahesh V.B. 
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - 'Clomiphene' (MRL 41 ) was administered to 120 patients with adequate follow-up. Of these patients 96 had primary, secondary or functional amenorrhoea. The remaining 24 patients were: women with regular cycles in whom suppression of ovulation was attempted; several children with sexual precocity in whom the antioesuogemc propel ties of ilie unit were studied; and a tew women with inadequate luteal phase. Dosage depended on the indication. The results were evaluated on the basis of: (i) temperature curve; (2) endometrial biopsies; (3) examination of cervical mucus; (4) vaginal smears; (5) urinary excretion of FSH, oestrogens and pregnanediol; (6) examination of ovaries after laparotomy, and (7) pregnancy after treatment. In the group of patients where ovulation was attempted, 71 menstruated once or several times. In 4 patients ovulation occurred, but without menstruation (temperature curve) and 4 showed signs of ovulation. Thirteen of the ovulating patients had one or more periods of anovulation. Eleven women became pregnant after treatment. Besides not flushes the main complication was cystic ovaries. If the temperature rose without menstruation following, systic ovaries could be expected. When treatment was discontinued the cysts disappeared spontaneously after a few weeks. In rats 'Clomiphene' appeared to have an oestrogcnic effect in the absence of oestrogens. If oestrogens were present its activity was inhibitory. In man small doses stimulated the production of LH, while large doses inhibited the production of LH and FSH. The anti-oestrogenic effect was demonstrated in vaginal smears, cervical mucus, the occurrence of hot flushes and the impossibility of suppressing ovulation if oestrogens were added. It proved impossible to increase the oestrogen level of women in the menopause, using this preparation. The drug has no androgenic or progestational effect. Various arguments support the conclusion that it can stimulate as well as inhibit the secretion of hypophyseal gonadotropins. It is not known whether the drug acts on the hypophysis or the hypothalamus.
