8939. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281485773
T1  - Steroid concentrations in normal follicular fluid and ovarian cyst fluid from cow
A1  - Short R.V. 
Y1  - 1962//
N2  - The following steroids were estimated in 5 samples of normal bovine follicular fluid, and in 24 samples of cyst fluid from cows with cystic ovaries: progesterone, 17a-hydroxyprogesterone (17 HP), androstenedione, oestrone and oestradiol-17beta. 2os-Hydroxypregn-4-en-3-one (20 HP) was also found in two samples of cyst fluid. No testosterone could be detected in any of the samples. Oestradiol-17beta was the major steroid present in all five samples of follicular fluid. Its concentration was significantly lower in the cyst fluid. Many of the cyst fluid samples contained large amounts of progesterone, but little or no detectable 17 HP, androstenedione, oestrone or oestradiol-17beta. Histological examination of the cyst wall in a number of these cases showed atretic or luteinization changes. In one case where luteinization had occurred, 20 HP was also present in the cyst fluid. The steroid concentra-tions in 9 'cyscic cows' with normal oastrous cycles did not differ significantlyfrom the concentrations in 7 nymphomaniac cows. The absolute concentrations and relative amounts of the various steroids differed greatly, both between animals and within the same animal. It is therefore concluded that the cyst itself is not the primary defect in cystic ovarian disease. Both histologically and endocrinologically the cyst appears to be a degenerative structure in which follicular growth continues whilst endocrine activity is waning.
