8943. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 280887153
T1  - THE BIRMINGHAM ORAL CONTRACEPTIVE TRIAL
A1  - Eckstein P.
A1  - Waterhouse J.A.H.
A1  - Bond G.M.
A1  - Mills W.G.
A1  - Sandilande D.M.
A1  - Shotton D.M. 
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - The main object of the trial (with norethynodrel) was to investigate the effect of lower doses with regard to suppression of ovulation and the incidence and severity of side effects. The women chosen for the trial were all under 36 years of age with at least one iving child and normal menstruation. In the first trial (48 women) the patients received tablets with 2.5 mg. norethynodrel (virtually 2.3 mg.) with 0.05 m g. (virtually 0.036 mg.)ethinyloestradiol-3- methylether (EO-3-ME) from day 5 to 24 of the cycle. Eight days after the last tablet a new course of tablets was started, independent of withdrawal bleeding. Later on this waa reduced to 6 days. In case of breakthrough bleeding the medication was stopped and started again on the fifth day of the bleeding with a new course of 20 tablets. In the event of amenorrhoea of more than 6 weeks an A-Z test was done and repeated at a few weeks interval until diagnosis was established. After 14 women had conceived, the trial was started with 5-mg. tablets and of the remaining 34 subjects nobody was pregnant after a year. As a method, the oral contraceptive was very well received, even when there were some side effects. Of the 14 conceptions 13 were accepted as a tablet failure, i. e.too low dosage. The children were born in good health and the girls showed no sign of virilization or other abnormality. The menstrual cycle was lengthened to about 35 days. In 37% there was some spotting and in 1/3 of the cases there was breakthrough bleeding. With the 5-mg.tablets only 2 patients stopped because of side effects (headache, nausea, swollen, tender breasts,backache and pelvic pain).The ineffectiveness of the 2.5 mg. tablets must be ascribed to the oestrogen content which was too low to be a contributory factor to an anovulation effect. The lengthening of the cycle suggests that the 2.5-mg.tablet did not suppress ovulation but merely delayed it to the following cycle.
