8952. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281175880
T1  - EFFECT of ULTRAHIGH FREQUENCY ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD upon CONCEPTION and COURSE of PREGNANCY in WHITE MICE (Russian text)
A1  - Povzhitkov V.A.
A1  - Tyagin N.V.
A1  - Greveshechnikova A.M. 
Y1  - 1961//
N2  - Experiments were conducted with two series of animals (20 experimental animals and 10 controls in each series) until the time of copulation. In the first series an irradiating beam of a density of 0. 344 mw. /sq. cm. was applied 20 times for 20 minutes each time, in the 2nd series a beam of the same density was applied 50 times for 30 minutes each time, and in a 3rd series a beam of a density of 50 mw. / sq. cm. was applied immediately after copulation (35 experimental animals and 19 controls) in the course of 12 days of pregnancy for 10 minutes daily. The results were as follows: a long-term exposure to an ultrahigh frequency field prior to copulation did not produce any effect upon the occurrence of pregnancy, just as it did not interrupt pregnancy, however, a tendency was discovered for pregnancy to extend past the term (the function of the afferent system of the uterus is apparently decreased as a result of changes occurring in the nervous system). The development of offspring whose mothers had been exposed to an ultrahigh frequency field prior to pregnancy occurred somewhat more rapidly than of those whose mothers had been exposed to such a field in the course of pregnancy; later on the development of baby mice took its normal course, however, it should be noted that they gained weight somewhat more slowly. The reaction to chor ionic-gonadotropin in a certain number of baby mice which were born to mothers who had been subjected to irradiation with an ultrahigh frequency field prior to the occurrence of pregnancy was negative, while in all controls it was positive. Patho-anatomically a slight cystic degeneration of ovaries was noted, with a decrease in their size and weight and haemorrhages in the horn of the uterus. More extensive changes in comparison with the controls took place in mice during the stages of pro-oestrus and oestrus, or in the meta-oestrus and dioestrus stages.
