8957. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281190876
T1  - Polycystic ovarian disease. A clinical and experimental study
A1  - Evans T.N.
A1  - Riley G.M. 
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - Forty patients with a diagnosis of polycystic ovarian disease had a wedge resection of the ovaries. The ages ranged from 17 to 40. After operation there were 36 ovulatory cycles. Thirty-seven pregnancies occurred in 21 patients. All patients had normal excretory rates of oestrogen and gonadotrophin. 17-Ketosteroid levels were normal or slightly elevated. In those cases tested, pregnanetriol values were all within normal limits. Pregnanediol levels were comparable to those found during the follicular phase of a normal menstrual cycle. In 2 patients LH excretion was comparable to that found in 3 normal patients during the pre- and postovulatory phases. A 3rd patient had slightly greater LH levels. The various theories of the aetiology of polycystic ovaries were reviewed. Animal experiments were performed on parabiont female rats. Ovaries were transplanted to spleen and kidneys. Collation of clinical and animal experiments suggest that the development of polycystic ovaries may result from continued exposure of the ovaries to gonadotrophic stimulation which is predominantly, but not exclusively, follicle-stimulating in nature. The stimulated follicles produce oestrogen in a relatively continuous manner still subject to a reciprocal relationship with pituitary gonadotrophin production. In an ovulatory cycle a single follicle dominates the cycle and the fluctuations in gonadotrophin and oestrogene are more pronounced than in an anovulatory cycle. A plausible explanation of the effects of wedge resection is that the excision results in a sudden reduction of oestrogen and the resulting increase in gonadotrophin stimulates a new crop of follicles with one destined for maturation. The success of wedge resection is dependent upon the creation of a physiological environment which permits normal follicle maturation.
