8963. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 280944932
T1  - Correlations between expired-alveolar and arterial pCO2 in normal subjects
A1  - Reichel G. 
Y1  - 1960//
N2  - In 20 subjects, the author compared different values of alveolar pCO 2 (pA CO2) measured on the curve obtained from a rapid infrared analyser, to the arterial pCO2 (paCO 2) and to the mixed venous pCO2, assumed to be 7 mm. Hg higher than the arterial pCO2. In the middle of a normal expiration, pA CO2, was 0.41 mm. Hg lower than Pa CO 2. At the end of a normal expiration pA CO2 was higher than pa CO2 by 0.53 mm. Hg. In a prolonged expiration, the gradient reached 5.25 after 6.4 sec., 6.90 after 13 sec. and at that time was close to the venous PCO2. PCO2 can equal Pa CO2 only if ventilation/perfusion relationships are normal in the lung as a whole. The relatively great dispersion of the difference between expired-alveolar and arterial PCO2 suggests that even in normal subjects there are in equal ventilation/perfusion relationships, which may result in a 2 mm. Hg gradient. (Following the author's communication, the conferees discussed the question of the normal arterial-alveolar gradient for CO2. Drs. E. A. Gaensler and A. Cournand questioned the validity of determining such small gradients when the errors of the method are likely to be as big as the gradient itself, and discussed the significance of mean values. Drs. Lacoste and Sadoul stressed the sensitivity of their analyser, the response time much quicker than with the Liston-Becker analyser and conventional recorders, and pointed out that the gradient depends on spatial as well as temporal factors, that the membrane component is practically inexistent, and that the distribution component is the major cause of the gradient, as studies in patients will now show.).
