8964. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281594515
T1  - An experimental study on acid-base balance in intracardiac surgery under induced ventricular fibrillation
A1  - Takase H. 
Y1  - 1959//
N2  - Fifty-six healthy adult dogs weighing 5-23 kg. were used to evaluate the acid-base balance during ventricular fibrillation induced during perfusion with an artificial heart-lung machine. In 17 dogs fibrillation was induced in the intact heart, while in the remainder (39) it was induced during open-heart surgery. (1) A decrease in pH and buffer bases and an increase in pCO 2 were the common findings observed in the first group. These changes were somewhat greater in those fibrillating for 10 min. under hypothermia than in those fibrillating for 3 min. at normal temperatures. These changes returned to normal after closure of the chest in all the normothermic and most of the hypothermic dogs. (2) The acidosis observed during open-heart surgery in the 29 animals was identical to that in the first group, and for animals recovered from these changes after closure of the chest, However, the mode of recovery varied with the operative procedure: Following the production of I. A. S. D. or I. V. S. D. these values returned to the preoperative level within 24 hr., while following formation of mitral stenosis it took about 7 days. In the 10 animals in which the artificial cardiac pathology was corrected, the recovery time was slightly shorter. In most of these animals these values returned to the preoperative level in 24 to 48 hr. (3) The fluctuation in O2 content was relatively slight except for a few cases in which marked fluctuation was noted. 100% O2 was given by artificial respiration in this study. (4) Out of 12 animals submitted to perfusion combined with hypothermia, 2 died: Both of them had marked disturbances in acid-base balance shortly before death. (5) Of the 29 dogs subjected to heart injury, 11 died: 3 of the 10 with I. A. S. D., 5 of the 12 with I. V. S. D., and 3 of the 7 with mitral stenosis. Of the 18 with fibrillation for 3-5 min. 6 died, and of the 11 fibrillating for 5-9 min. 5 dogs died. The acid-base balance was abnormal in 6 of the 11 which died: 2 were direct deaths within 3 days from recurrence of fibrillation, haemothorax and poor expansion of the lungs, and 4 were early deaths. But no acid-base balance disorders were found in the other 5 cases, which died of pyothorax during the 2nd week. (6) Of the 10 dogs in which the cardiac pathology was corrected 4 died: one within 24 hr. after ligation of the right coronary artery, 2 from haemothorax (these had disturbances in the acid-base balance prior to death) and one from pyothorax on the 10th postoperative day (no marked impairment in acid-base balance on the 7th postoperative day).
