8968. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 280872835
T1  - Physiological aspects of artificial ventilation
A1  - Nunn J.F. 
Y1  - 1957//
N2  - In order to understand what actually happens during artificial respiration, it is necessary to have a basic knowledge of the elastic and viscous resistances of the lungs and airways. These qualities can be imitated by means of an electric circuit, in which the voltage represents the pressure, the ohms the resistance, the amperes the air flow, the coulombs the gas volume and the capacity of condensers the compliance of lungs and thorax. The gas exchange is governed by 3 factors: ventilation, distribution and diffusion. Of more importance than the total ventilation is the alveolar ventilation. In this respect the anatomical and the physiological dead space are of interest. In hyperventilated alveoli the alveolar dead space is increased. Under these circumstances the arterial Pco, is higher than the alveolar Pco2. Relative overperfusion of alveoli has the same effect as an increase of the venous admixture. In cases of perfusion of non-ventilated alveoli oxygen therapy has no use, while in cases of a relative overperfusion of a considerable number of alveoli oxygen therapy is indicated. Unequal distribution affects the arterial Po2, more than the Pco2. Use of the Pco1 for monitoring ventilation is advocated. Different techniques of estimating this Pco, and their failures are described. A respiratory alkalosis is compensated for by a metabolic acidosis, while respiratory acidosis is compensated for by a metabolic alkalosis. This compensating mechanisms make it difficult to interpret the meaning of the alkali reserve. A diagram is shown which gives help in deducing both the respiratory and metabolic imbalances.
