Y1  - 1957//
N2  - A report about 4 siblings, 2 brothers and 2 sisters suffering from typical dystrophia myotonica. Description of the clinical picture and laboratory examinations of all 4 patients and of the autopsy findings in 3 of them. Case 2, born in 1910, had urinary androgens as androsterone 4.8 mg. in 24 hr. He died at the age of 43. Case 3, born in 1911, had 6.6 mg. androsterone in 24 hr. and diabetes. He died at the age of 46. Case 4, born in 1913, died in 1943. The authors support the opinion in the literature that dystrophia myotonica is of endocrine origin as the fronto-temporal baldness, the testicular atrophy, obesity and decreased 17-ketosteroids are in favour of this theory. They found in their cases: muscular changes typical for dystrophia myotonica in all 3 cases, tubular atrophy of testicles and cellular changes in pituitary with increase in basophilic cells in both male cases, hypoplasia and lipid paucity of adrenal cortex in all 3 patients, diffuse colloidal struma in both male patients, cystic degeneration and hypoplasia of ovaries in the female case, hyperplastic thymus in one male and absent thymus in the other male and in the female case. Smooth muscles were not affected.
