8970. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281475278
T1  - Multiple primary malignancies. A case report of four in succession
A1  - Maddock W.G.
A1  - Lipinski J.T.
A1  - Lien R.C.
A1  - Alt H.L. 
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - The authors report a case of 4 metachronous (successive) primary malignancies. Four other cases collected from the literature are summarized in graph form. The patient, a 64-year-old housewife, had had a radical mastectomy of the right breast at the age of 38 for undifferentiated-cell carcinoma of the comedo type. At the age of 51 a panhysterosalpingo-oophorectomy, bilateral, had been performed for papillary cystadenoma of the right ovary with malignant degeneration. At the age of 58 the patient had had a segmental resection of sigmoid colon and upper rectum for carcinoma of sigmoid colon. At the age of 59 a left radical mastectomy for adenocarcinoma, duct cell type, grade III, of the breast was done. Six years later she showed signs of pulmonary and liver metastasis. At autopsy a year later the lungs, liver, and retroperitoneal lymph nodes were extensively infiltrated by duct-cell sclerosing carcinoma similar to the 4th malignancy of the breast. The article then discusses the incidence, average age and heredity factor, predisposition, mode of origin, and sites of multiple carcinoma. The consensus seems to favour the theory that the actual incidence of multiple cancer is greater then can be accounted for on the basis of the law of chance which has been variously estimated in the neighbourhood of 3%. The authors believe that the apparent and actual incidence of multiple cancer should gradually rise because: (1) Progressive improvements in methods for accumulating accurate cancer statistics should bring more cases to light. (2) Progressive education of the laity and the medical profession should result in earlier diagnosis and treatment. (3) Progressive increase in number of persons living in the 'cancer age' group should result in an increase in incidence of multiple primary cancer. (4) Newer methods of treatment of existing cancers should lengthen survival times and increase cure rates, thus affording greater opportunity for multiple growths to occur.
