8971. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281441805
T1  - Structure and functional capacity of the ovaries of higher polyploids (4N, 5N) in the Mexican axolotl (Siredon or Ambystoma mexicanum)
A1  - Humphrey R.R.
A1  - Fankhauser G. 
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - In the Mexican axolotl, tetraploids of spontaneous origin are occasionally found in spawnings of diploids; far more, however, appear in the progeny of triploid females mated with diploid males. Of 50 reared, 40 were females. Ovaries of tetraploids develop in essentially normal fashion except for the degeneration of large numbers of oocytes following synapsis. Enough ova escape this degeneration and attain maturity to permit spawning at the end of the first year. The average number of eggs ovulated in 24 spawnings was 225. About 170 axolotl pentaploids have been identified in spawnings from diploid parents and only 8 among the offspring of tetraploid females mated with diploid males. Of 30 in which sex was ascertained, 29 were females, only one lived longer than 2 yr. In the ovaries of pentaploids, only a very few oocytes escape degeneration. As a result, the ovaries are functionally sterile. Ectopic transplants of the ovaries into ovariectomized diploids similarly fail to attain a functional state. In the absence of convincing evidence that the greater loss of oocytes in pentaploids as compared with triploids or tetraploids is due to intersexuality or to nutritional or hormonal deficiencies, it is concluded that it results from the more serious disturbance of synapsis and subsequent developmental processes incident to the presence in these cells of a greater number of additional sets of chromosomes.
