8972. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281253792
T1  - Alveolar carbon dioxide levels in pregnant, parturient and lactating subjects
A1  - Boutourline-Young H.
A1  - Boutourline-Young E. 
Y1  - 1956//
N2  - A 588 series of measurements was made of the partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the alveolar gas of 16 women during pregnancy and in 13 of these during and following childbirth. A 64 series of observations was also made upon 3 control subjects, one male, one menstruating female and one lactating menstruating female. In pregnant subjects the level of pCO2 falls steadily to a mean level of 30-32 mm. Hg in the final 12 weeks where it remains stable. Significant cyclic fluctuations of the pCO2 were not observed in the last 24 weeks of pregnancy. The falls of pCO2 observed during labour have been significantly correlated with the caloric intake during the 24 hr. prior to parturition. The falls in pCO2 observed subsequently to parturition have a significant relationship with length of labour and with caloric intake during the 24 hr. prior to parturition. The rise of pCO 2 to normal levels following parturition is strongly influenced by the maternal diet, during this period; the more adequate the diet, the faster the rise. Significant regular fluctuations of pCO2 levels during the menstrual cycle were observed in the 2 female controls. On the basis of this experimental work and the information at present available upon neonatal respiratory physiology, a hypothesis has been constructed to account, in part, for the condition of relative acidosis of the newborn.
