N2  - This volume of 1323 pages contains the main lectures and papers presented at the International Congress on Gynaecology and Obstetrics held at Geneva from July 26-31, 1954. 'Prophylaxis' is taken in a very broad sense, as may be judged from the introductory paper by Sigerist on 'The rise of Preventive Medicine in the World' and from those by Hussay (Adrenal tumours with oestrogen activity in castrated animals) and by Caspersson (Cytochemical approach to problems of tumour growth and diagnosis). The articles are written in English, French, German, Italian and Spanish, but each contains a summary in either English or French or both. The following subdivisions are made: Uterine cancer (Tesauro, Detection of uterine cancer by means of cytological tests; Dellepiane, Karyocytological investigations in the early diagnosis of uterine cancer; Runge, Possibilities and methods of prevention of uterine carcinoma). Cancer of the cervix (Gagnon, Marital state and pregnancy and their role in the development of cancer in the uterine cervix; Ayre, Cervical carcinogenesis, stress and adaptation factors, regression studies; Hinselmann. From the primitive lightcolposcope to the television-colposcope; White, Practical experience with the Papanicolaou-Traut vaginal smear; Kasdon, Enzymes and cytology in the diagnosis of in situ cancer of the uterine cervix; Bacialli, Cytology and colpo-microscopy in the diagnosis of uterine cancer; Salaber and Calandra. The value of auxiliary methods in the early diagnosis of cancer of the uterine cervix; Magendie, Carcinoma of the cervix, detection at an early stage; Funck-Brentano. Methods for the diagnosis of dystrophic cervica lesions; Hiffmac, Farelland Mahn. Differential diagnosis of carcinoma in situ of the cervix uteri; Moricard, Anomalies, of the number and position of the chromosomes in tin, lu,nosis of the intra-epithelial squamous-cell carcinoma of til ,cervix ut-,o; Hansen, Jennings and Wood, Differential diagnosis and treatment of lesi