8979. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Classic <1947 to 1973> Part 1 of 2
AN  - 281607572
T1  - Evaluation of the basal body temperature. An analysis of 1012 basal body temperature recordings
A1  - Siegler S.L.
A1  - Siegler A.M. 
Y1  - 1951//
N2  - Analyses were made of 1.012 graphs submitted by 202 women, 20 to 36 years of age, who where infertile for functional rather than organic causes. Included were 25 women in whom the infertility was due to seminal inadequacies. Of the 1,012 cycles, 712 71% were biphasic and 300 or 29% were monophasic. The latter group included basal body temperatures recorded during 176 months of pregnancy. When the pregnancy graphs were excluded, there were 766 or 85.2% biphasic cycles and 70 or 14.8% monophasic cycles. Of 132 women with biphasic curves, 109 or 82% became pregnant, whereas in 56 women with monophasic-biphasic cycles, 28 or 50% conceived. Three women conceived during monophasic cycles indicating that ovulation per se may not in. itself call for the biphasic type of temperature graph. A study of the biphasic curves revealed that the average oestrogenic, or low phase, was 16.5 days but varied from 5 to 40 days. The variation in the length of the menstrual cycle is due principally to the variability of the low temperature phase. We have no way of accurately predicting when the shifts in temperature will occur. As to the pre-ovulatory dip in temperature some of the graphs showed that the temperature preceding the rise is only slightly, if any, lower than that recorded on the several preceding days. Not infrequently the temperature rises after a low point and then falls again and a day or more elapses before the temperature reaches a high level which it maintains until just before menstruation. There is as yet no proof that ovulation per se is directly connected with the thermal shift. The criterion of an adequate thermal shift was taken as 0.4degree F. and less than 2 days was considered an adequate rate of rise. The thermal shift took from 1 to 11 days and the mean was 3.5 in duration. Only 33% of the cases showed the so-called 'rapid shift' of less than 2 days .In 94 or 67% of the 140 cases of conception there was a slow temperature shift. In 3 women pregnancy occurred during a monophasic or anovulatory cycle. Luteinization of the graafian follicle with no rupture can occur and the basal body temperature in no way detects whether or not ovulation actually takes place. In contra-distinction to the oestrogenic phase, the luteal phase is more constant but presents a definite variability. Of the authors' cases 62% had an inadequate luteal phase of less than 12 days. Endometrial biopsies at the time of menstruation of 22 patients showing biphasic graphs, and a relatively low luteal phase rise in temperature, showed that 18 were of the proliferative and 4 of the immature progestational type. This suggests that the theca cells of an unruptured follicle may become luteinized and the liberated hormones may produce only a temperature rise. When the high phase of temperature elevation was prolonged for 20 days, a diagnosis of pregnancy was made with a high degree of accuracy. The temperature gradually fell at about the fourth month from the high phase to the low phase. In 12 women observed to actual delivery, the basal body temperature gave no indication as to when labour might ensue. The temperature curve did not reflect the seriousness of a threatened abortion nor the presence of an unruptured ectopic pregnancy.
